# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adolf-hitler
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] The document is nine pages long; it is undated and did not identify a specific author.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] The document laid out a plan for the storming and occupation of eight key buildings (designated as "Targeted Buildings") in the District of Columbia on January 6, 2021.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] The target locations were the Russell, Dirksen, and Hart Senate office buildings; the U.S.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] Supreme Court Building; the Cannon, Longworth, and Rayburn House office buildings; and the CNN's D.C. office building.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] A section titled the "Patriot Plan" was intended for public distribution, calling on people to gather at 1 p.m. on January 6 and await a signal to attack, with a demand to nullify the elections results and have the military hold a new election.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] The author of *1776 Returns* has not been confirmed.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] However, Flores sent the document to Tarrio a week before the January 6 attacks.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] After the attack, Flores agreed to an informal, untranscribed appearance in early 2022 with House Select Committee on the January 6 Attack investigators, in which she named Samuel Armes as the author of the document.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] Armes, like Flores, is a cryptocurrency advocate.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] January 6 Committee investigators interviewed Armes in July 2022.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] He denied drafting the "1776 Returns" document and claimed that Flores was "blame-shifting" by attributing authorship to him.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] However, Flores acknowledged that in summer 2020, he drafted a "war gaming" plan and then shared it with Flores by Google Drive.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] Armes told investigators that the document was between three and five pages and explored "a scenario where a certain president doesn't leave the White House or there is just mad chaos in the streets because no one knows who's in charge".
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] He indicated that he indirectly provided inspiration for the nine-page "1776 Returns" document; in the interview with investigators, he distinguished between "aspects that he said he had written from components he said he did not".
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] He said that he "never imagined that" what he had written would ultimately be "turned into" an operational plan to attack federal buildings.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] In the interview, Armes said he had a slight acquaintance with Tarrio through their mutual friendship with Flores.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] Prosecutors later subpoenaed Flores to testify before a federal grand jury investigating Tarrio and the Proud Boys' role in the attacks; she refused to testify, invoking her Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] In all, more than 30 Proud Boys were charged with crimes in connection with the January 6 attack.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] The "1776 Returns" document was one of many pieces of evidence in the trial of Tarrio and four lieutenants: Ethan Nordean, Joe Biggs, Zachary Rehl and Dominic Pezzola.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] It was cited in the indictment of defendants and in court filings.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] The existence of the document was first reported in March 2022 in the *New York Times*, and the full document became public in June 2022, when Rehl's attorneys submitted it as an exhibit to a motion asking for pretrial release.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] In May 2023, following a lengthy trial, a jury convicted Tarrio, Nordean, Biggs, and Rehl guilty of seditious conspiracy, among other crimes; Pezzola was acquitted of seditious conspiracy but convicted of other felonies.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] During the trial, the prosecutors introduced text message correspondence between Flores and Tarrio, in which Flores touted her 1776 Returns document and wrote, "If you don't like my plan, let me know.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] But I want you to be the executor and benefactor of my brilliance." During his trial, Tarrio declined to testify in his own defense.
[src:adolf-hitler/1776-returns] Outside court, however, Tarrio claimed he never opened or used the *1776 Returns* document, but records showed that Tarrio used the phrase "the Winter Palace" in discussions with his associate before and after January 6, and Tarrio did Google searches for "The Winter Palace" during that time.
[src:adolf-hitler/1919-german-presidential-election] The **1919 German presidential election** (*Reichspräsidentenwahl*) was the first election to the office of President of the Reich (*Reichspräsident*), Germany's head of state during the 1919−1933 Weimar Republic.
[src:adolf-hitler/1919-german-presidential-election] The constitution that stipulated a direct popular vote was not completed before 11 August 1919.
[src:adolf-hitler/1919-german-presidential-election] Because a head of state was needed immediately the 1919 presidential election was held indirectly, by the National Assembly, on 11 February 1919.
[src:adolf-hitler/1919-german-presidential-election] The winner was SPD chairman Friedrich Ebert, who beat former (Imperial) Secretary of the Interior Arthur von Posadowsky-Wehner in the first round of voting by 277 to 49 votes.
[src:adolf-hitler/1919-german-presidential-election] Ebert was supported by the SPD, the German Centre Party and the German Democratic Party (DDP), the parties of the "Weimar Coalition", which held more than 77 per cent of the seats in the National Assembly.
[src:adolf-hitler/1919-german-presidential-election] He became President of Germany, holding the office until his death in 1925.
[src:adolf-hitler/1919-german-presidential-election] With the subsequent 1925 and 1932 German presidential elections held with direct universal suffrage, this election would be the sole indirect presidential election held until the end of World War II.
[src:adolf-hitler/1919-german-presidential-election] Further, Ebert would also remain the sole Social Democrat elected President of Germany until the election of Gustav Heinemann in 1969, and the only socialist to serve in that position between 1919 and the end of the war in 1945.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] A presidential election was held in Germany on 29 March 1925, with a runoff on 26 April.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] It was the first direct election to the office of president of Germany (*Reichspräsident*), the head of state of the Weimar Republic, and followed the death in office of Friedrich Ebert.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The first round of the election included seven candidates and resulted in no clear frontrunner.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] In the second round, the centrist parties united around Wilhelm Marx of the Catholic Centre Party, while the parties of the Right convinced former field marshal Paul von Hindenburg, who had not run in the first round, to enter the contest.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Germany's first president, Friedrich Ebert of the Social Democratic Party (SPD), was elected indirectly by the Weimar National Assembly on 11 February 1919.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The Weimar Constitution, which became effective six months later, required that the president be elected by the "whole German people".
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The first regular presidential election was to have taken place in 1920, but it was repeatedly postponed because of Germany's continuing political unrest.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] In late 1922, the Reichstag extended Ebert's term to 30 June 1925, a change which required amending Article 180 of the constitution.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] When Ebert died in office on 28 February 1925, Chancellor Hans Luther, an independent, took over the duties of the office under Article 51 of the Weimar Constitution.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The Law on the Deputization of the Reich President of 10 March 1925 then made the president of the Reich Court, Walter Simons, acting president of Germany.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The election was scheduled for 29 March 1925.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The president was directly elected by universal adult suffrage for a term of seven years.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The Weimar Republic used a modified two-round system for the election of the president.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] If no candidate received an absolute majority of votes in the first round, a second ballot would take place in which the candidate with a plurality of votes would be elected.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] There was no prohibition against a candidate who had not run in the first round being nominated for the second.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Ebert died four months before his term was due to expire.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Up to that point, there had been little discussion of a possible successor, and only a month was allotted to select candidates and hold the campaign.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The centrist parties recognized the advantage of fielding a joint candidate but were unable to overcome their divisions.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The parties to the Right, the German National People's Party (DNVP) and German People's Party (DVP), wanted chiefly to keep the presidency out of the hands of the Social Democrats and were willing to work with the German Democratic Party (DDP) and Centre Party to do so.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Defense Minister Otto Gessler of the DDP was proposed as a compromise candidate, but Foreign Minister Gustav Stresemann of the DVP opposed him out of concern that choosing a defense minister would negatively affect Germany's foreign policy.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] In the end, only three right-of-center parties were able to unite around a common candidate.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The German-Hanoverian Party supported Heinrich Held.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Most völkisch movement parties supported Jarres as a compromise candidate, although Adolf Hitler and the Nazi Party (NSDAP) supported Ludendorff.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The frontrunners in the highly fragmented election were the candidates of the Right (Jarres) and Left (Braun).
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] While the total votes for the Centre Party (-5.6%) and DDP (-18.3%) dropped from the Reichstag election of December 1924, the parties of the far Left and far Right fell considerably more in percentage terms.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The Communist Party's vote total dropped by 30.9%, and the far Right's showing was down 68.5%.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] It was a continuation of the trend towards de-radicalization that had become visible between the closely spaced Reichstag elections in May and December 1924 and can be attributed to the economic stabilization that was taking place at the time.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The formation of united blocs was even more important in the second round because the candidate with the most votes, even if not over 50%, won the election.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The parties of the Weimar Coalition – SPD, DDP, and Centre – knew that unity was their only chance of defeating the candidate chosen by the Right.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The SPD, which was aware that its endorsement carried significant weight only among its own party members, dropped its support of Otto Braun and made a political deal with the Centre Party to support Wilhelm Marx.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Braun had resigned as minister-president of Prussia in January after a tied vote of no-confidence against his ministry.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] A series of indecisive votes in the Prussian Landtag that swung between Marx and Braun then followed.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The SPD promised the Centre Party that it would back Marx in the presidential election in exchange for the Centre's support for Braun as minister-president of Prussia.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The DDP then joined them in the *Volksblock* to endorse Marx as candidate for president.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The parties of the Right united around the 78-year-old World War I field marshal Paul von Hindenburg.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] In spite of the eventual consensus among the parties to support him, there were misgivings about his candidacy on a number of fronts.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Stresemann and the DVP initially opposed him due to worries that the western powers would see him as a provocation.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Large industrialists, who bore much of the cost of the campaign and generally were aligned with the DNVP, feared that Hindenburg, whose family owned a large estate east of the Elbe, would favor eastern agrarians.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Wilhelm von Gayl of the DNVP expressed concern over whether Hindenburg would be willing to openly violate the constitution as some monarchists and anti-republicans hoped he would.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] In the end, he was endorsed by all of the parties of the Right, including the German Völkisch Freedom Party (DVFP), the Nazi Party and the Bavarian People's Party.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The BVP, which represented heavily Catholic Bavaria, split from the Centre Party and Marx, who was Catholic, because it believed that the Protestant Hindenburg would be more certain to oppose the Social Democrats.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Hindenburg, at his own insistence, obtained the approval of former emperor Wilhelm II before he agreed to run for president.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The Communist Party alone put forward its own candidate, Ernst Thälmann, even though the Communist International (Comintern) had urged the KPD not to do so.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] In an appeal to German workers, the KPD stated that "it is not the task of the proletariat to choose the most skilful representative of bourgeois interests, [or] to choose the lesser evil between the civil dictator Marx and the military dictator Hindenburg...
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Marx was not considered to be an especially inspired campaigner, and Hindenburg, who had no experience as a politician, made few personal appearances.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] He addressed only one public meeting, held in Hanover, where he had retired, and gave one radio address.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Hindenburg stated that he would uphold the constitution, and his campaign stressed his devotion to "social justice, religious equality [and] genuine peace at home and abroad" and called for a "national community" (*Volksgemeinschaft*) under his leadership.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The parties of the bourgeois Right campaigned for him as a man who stood above party politics and condemned Marx for being too close to the SPD.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] In the words of Fritz Schäffer of the BVP, Hindenburg's candidacy emerged out of the "misery of Germany's party politics".
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The second round was held on 26 April, with a turnout of 77.6%.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Hindenburg won on a plurality of the vote, with 48.3% to Marx's 45.3% and Thälmann's 6.4%.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The KPD clearly played a spoiler role in the election – the 27 April headline in the SPD's party newspaper *Vorwärts* read "Hindenburg by the Grace of Thälmann!" – although Thälmann's votes did not all come from committed KPD members.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Religion also was part of many voters' considerations.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] When compared to the SPD's results in the first round, Marx fared especially poorly in Saxony, where strong anti-clerical sentiment led many SPD voters to turn to Thälmann.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] In Protestant regions of Württemberg, many liberal and socialist voters turned to Hindenburg for the same reason.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] In East Prussia, Hindenburg as the victor of the Battle of Tannenberg, which was fought in East Prussia, drew many who had voted for one of the Weimar parties (SPD, DDP and Centre) in the first round.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Across Germany as a whole, Hindenburg had more success at bringing first round non-voters to the polls than did Marx.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Some also attributed Marx's loss to the candidature of Ernst Thälmann of the Communist Party of Germany, who did not drop out in the second round.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] However, historian Peter Fritzsche rejected this view, calling the claim "far-fetched" and arguing that "given the explicit enmity of this party toward the Weimar "capitalist state," it would have been completely unrealistic to expect the KPD to support the candidate of the Weimar system".
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Fritsche instead found that the BVP's endorsement of Hindenburg was crucial to Marx's defeat.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] In spite of Hindenburg's open monarchism and pressure from some of the men in his inner circle, Hindenburg as president never overtly stepped outside of constitutional bounds during his term in office.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] After the Great Depression hit Germany in 1929, he allowed Chancellor Heinrich Brüning to govern by presidential decree rather than through the Reichstag, but under Article 48, his actions were within the letter if not necessarily the spirit of the constitution.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] The 1930 Reichstag election made the Nazi Party the second strongest in the parliament, but its rise was due primarily to the dire economic circumstances under which the nation was suffering.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Hindenburg was re-elected president in 1932.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] He was supported in that election even by the Social Democrats as the only candidate who could defeat Adolf Hitler.
[src:adolf-hitler/1925-german-presidential-election] Winners within each constituency are highlighted in the color representing the party.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in Germany on 20 May 1928 to elect the fourth Reichstag of the Weimar Republic.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] It resulted in a significant shift to the left, with gains for the socialists and communists and losses for the nationalists.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The centre-right government of Wilhelm Marx was replaced by a centre-left grand coalition government led by Hermann Müller of the Social Democratic Party (SPD).
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] During the almost four years since the previous Reichstag election in December 1924, Germany had been governed by four conservative cabinets, two of which included the radical nationalist German National People's Party (DNVP).
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] None of them involved the Social Democratic Party (SPD), which had the most seats of any party in the Reichstag.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The final cabinet of Wilhelm Marx of the Catholic Centre Party collapsed in February 1928 due to a dispute over education policy, and an election was called for May.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] In social and economic terms, the election took place at the height of the Weimar Republic's economic stabilization.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The economy was developing positively and unemployment figures were lower than in previous years.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The SPD, which had not led a government since mid-1920 nor participated in a cabinet since 1923, had made it clear in its 1927 party conference in Kiel that it was ready to take over a governing role again.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] Along with the Communist Party of Germany (KPD), the SPD centred its campaign around opposition to expanding the German Navy.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] Specifically at issue was funding the construction of the armoured cruiser A, which the SPD, KPD and German Democratic Party (DDP) had argued against during the final days of the Marx cabinet.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] Because the majority in the Reichstag had voted to cut subsidies for school children's meals while expressing approval for funding for the ship, first the KPD and then the SPD used the slogan "Food for children instead of armoured cruisers" (*Kinderspeisung statt Panzerkreuzer*) in their campaigns.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The Centre Party saw no possibility of pushing through its denominational school law in a centre-left coalition.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The DDP, besides criticizing the naval expansion, advocated a grand coalition.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The German People's Party (DVP) relied on the popularity of Foreign Minister Gustav Stresemann in the election campaign.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] He, too, thought that there was no reasonable alternative to a grand coalition.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] In the power struggle that had been taking place at the top of the DNVP since 1927, the extreme faction led by the pan-German publisher Alfred Hugenberg had gained more and more influence, and the party sought to win back or retain voters who had been disappointed by its radicalism.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The NSDAP had consolidated its position on the extreme right.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The Reichstag was elected via party list proportional representation.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] For this purpose, the country was divided into 35 multi-member electoral districts.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] A party was entitled to a seat for every 60,000 votes won.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] This was calculated via a three-step process on the constituency level, an intermediate level which combined multiple constituencies, and finally nationwide, where all parties' excess votes were combined.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] In the third nationwide step, parties could not be awarded more seats than they had already won on the two lower constituency levels.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] Due to the fixed number of votes per seat, the size of the Reichstag fluctuated between elections based on the number of voters.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] People who were incapacitated according to the Civil Code, who were under guardianship or provisional guardianship, or who had lost their civil rights after a criminal court ruling were not eligible to vote.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The results were a defeat for the parties of the ruling centre-right.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The DNVP particularly suffered, falling to 14% of the vote and losing 30 seats.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The German Democratic Party and the conservative German People's Party had more modest losses of seven and six seats respectively.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The Catholic Centre Party, which lost eight seats, saw a decline in its Reichstag membership for the first time since 1920.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The winners of the election were the parties of the left.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The SPD, in opposition since 1923, won 30% of the vote, up 5.5% since the previous election.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The Communist Party also improved, to 10.6% from 8.9%.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] With a strong left wing and splintered right, there was little alternative to a government led by the SPD.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] Social Democrat Hermann Müller, who had served briefly as chancellor in 1920, was charged with forming a new cabinet.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The only viable majority was a great coalition stretching from the SPD to the DVP.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] Negotiations proved difficult: it took two weeks for the cabinet to be formed and sworn in, and then only as a "cabinet of personalities" rather than a formal coalition.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] It included ministers from the SPD, DVP, DDP and Bavarian People's Party (BVP).
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The Centre sent only one minister, Theodor von Guérard, as a so-called "observer".
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] It was not until ten months later, in April 1929, that a coalition agreement could be signed and the Centre Party officially enter the cabinet.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The second Müller cabinet was the final democratic government of the Weimar Republic.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] Its fall in March 1930 marked the end of the parliamentary system and the beginning of the presidential cabinets that preceded the Nazi takeover in 1933.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The Centre Party's and Bavarian People's Party's performance in the election raised long term concerns over their futures.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The parties had suffered heavy losses but more importantly the parties historic dominance over the Catholic vote had further diminished.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] Falling from a historical high of 85% in 1870 to 55% in 1912 to only 48% in the 1928 election.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] This number had been increased by the passage of Woman's Suffrage after World War 1, with only 39% of male Catholic voters supporting the parties in the election.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] The two parties losses came some several places: middle class voters had defected to the Economic Party, workers in Westphalia and the Rhineland had defected to the SPD, and they had lost support among rural voters.
[src:adolf-hitler/1928-german-federal-election] But they all underscored the fundamental problem that an ever increasing amount of German Catholics were prioritizing their economic interests over their religious identity.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] A referendum on the Young Plan was held in Germany on 22 December 1929.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] It was an attempt to use popular legislation to annul the Young Plan agreement between the German government and the World War I opponents of the German Empire regarding the amount and conditions of reparations payments.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The referendum was the result of the initiative "Against the Enslavement of the German People (Freedom Act)" launched in 1929 by right-wing parties and organizations.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] It called for an overall revision of the Treaty of Versailles and stipulated that government officials who accepted new reparation obligations would be committing treason.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Eligible voters had from 16 to 29 October to sign the initiative and register their support for the draft Freedom Act.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] With just over 10% of those eligible to vote signing, the minimum requirement to pass the initiative was narrowly met.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The German Reichstag debated the draft on 29 and 30 November, and it was rejected by a majority of deputies.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The initiators then requested a referendum, which took place on 22 December.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Since the Reich government had judged the Freedom Act to be unconstitutional, the decision required approval by a majority of all those eligible to vote instead of just the votes cast.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Even though 94.5% of those voting supported the referendum, it failed due to the low turnout of just under 15% of eligible voters.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The initiative and referendum were nevertheless significant for the political development of the following years.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The propaganda campaign led by the political right was one of the largest of its kind during the Weimar Republic, and the government responded with considerable counter-propaganda.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] For the first time the traditional right, such as the German National People's Party (DNVP), acted together with the Nazi Party (NSDAP).
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The significance that the referendum had for the rise of Adolf Hitler and the Nazi party is disputed historically.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] One of the problems that weighed most heavily on the Weimar Republic's domestic politics was the reparations that the German Reich had to pay under Article 231 of the Treaty of Versailles as a result of its defeat in World War I.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] There were repeated foreign policy disputes between Germany and the victorious powers over the amount of the payments, which had first been set at 132 billion gold marks in the London Payment Plan of 1921.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] When Germany failed to meet its payment obligations in 1923, French and Belgian troops occupied the Ruhr, in part to take reparations payments in goods such as coal.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In 1924 international commissions of experts examined Germany's economic strength and drew up proposals for the payment of reparations.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The results were the Dawes Plan and the London Agreement of 1924, which for the first time led to regular German payments.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] For what was intended to be a final settlement of the reparations question, another international commission of experts drafted the Young Plan (named after American industrialist Owen D.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Young) in Paris between February and June 1929.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] At two government-level international conferences in The Hague in August 1929 and January 1930, the amount of German reparation debt was reduced to the equivalent of 36 billion Reichsmarks.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The annual payments were lower than in the Dawes Plan, but they were to run until 1988.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] It was nevertheless to Germany's advantage that the reparations commission and all international economic controls were eliminated, giving the country back a large share of its sovereignty.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In addition, acceptance of the plan meant that the Rhineland, occupied by Allied troops since 1920, would be vacated ahead of schedule.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The government highlighted these advantages in its disputes with its opponents.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Particular emphasis was placed on the lower payments and the resulting relief to the Reich budget.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The Young Plan is considered the last success of the policy of rapprochement of Foreign Minister Gustav Stresemann of the German People's Party (DVP), who died before its final adoption on 3 October 1929.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Domestic political disputes about the Young Plan began in the summer of 1929.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Much of the public was appalled by the long duration and the total amount of payments to which Germany had committed itself.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The sum of all annual payments came to 115 billion Reichsmarks, and since total Reich revenue in the fiscal year 1929–30 was 7.73 billion Reichsmarks, the figure seemed very high.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The political right was able to make use of the agreement for propaganda purposes.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] It conjured up the image of grandsons up to their necks in debt at birth.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The fight against the Young Plan offered itself as a point around which the divided right wing could crystallize in order to be able to strike out at the hated system of the "November criminals" – the government leaders who had signed the Armistice of 11 November 1918.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Representatives of agriculture and heavy industry in particular opposed the plans.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The Reich Committee of German Agriculture called them economically unacceptable.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The Association for the Protection of Common Economic Interests in the Rhineland and Westphalia passed a resolution claiming that the Young Plan would impose "unbearable burdens" on the German economy.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Industry's opposition was, however, by no means unanimous.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] It was primarily heavy industry that opposed the Young Plan.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In the business community as a whole, approval tended to dominate since the plan was associated with financial relief.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Alfred Hugenberg, a media baron and chairman of the German National People's Party (DNVP), had led the party on a radical course against the Weimar Republic after the party's losses in the 1928 Reichstag elections.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In January 1929 Hugenberg was seeking to rally the political right, and the fight against the Young Plan seemed a likely means to do so.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] At the same time he was leading an intra-party conflict to bring the German nationalist Reichstag faction under Kuno von Westarp under his control.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Hugenberg controlled a large number of newspapers and news services, including Germany's most important film company, UFA.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Through them he had a strong influence on the formation of public opinion.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In June 1929 Hugenberg put together a "Reich Committee for the German People's Initiative against the Young Plan and the War Guilt Lie".
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The first meeting was attended by Heinrich Class of the Pan-German League, Franz Seldte of the Stahlhelm, a veterans' association closely associated with the DNVP, Martin Schiele (DNVP) and Karl Hepp (DVP) for the Agricultural League, and, thanks to Hugenberg's invitation, Adolf Hitler of the NSDAP.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Hugenberg admired the Nazis' dynamism and youthful enthusiasm and hoped to use them as a 'drum' in the campaign against the Young Plan.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The Reich Committee also included Fritz Thyssen of the Reich Association of German Industry, and the industrialist and co-founder of the German People's Party (DVP) Albert Vögler, who had participated in the expert consultations at the Paris conference but had resigned in protest.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] At the first meeting, a working committee (presidium) of 16 people was elected, among them Adolf Hitler.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In addition to the leading representatives mentioned above, the presidium included members of the participating political parties.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The actual tone, however, was set by the two chairmen of the executive committee, Seldte and Hugenberg.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The committee was financed primarily by businesses.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The Reich Committee divided the funds among the parties and organizations involved.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] There is no evidence of favoritism towards the NSDAP as some have claimed.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The goal was not just to prevent the Young Plan's reparations clauses from being implemented.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] They believed that accepting the Young Plan meant confessing to the 'war guilt clause', which had not been modified under the Young Plan, and wanted to explicitly reject it.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In addition they wished to topple the government led by Hermann Müller of the Social Democratic Party (SPD) and to hold new elections.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The course of action did not meet with everyone's approval even in the Reich Committee's more conservative camp.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] After Hitler's failed 1923 Beer Hall Putsch, the German National People's Party (DNVP) had severed its ties to the National Socialists until Hugenberg restored them by including the NSDAP in the Reich Referendum Committee.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Although he was fundamentally opposed to democracy and against popular legislation, Hitler participated because he expected political advantages from it.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Until then he had been regarded as a Bavarian beer hall bigwig (*bayerische Bierkellergröße*) who headed a comparatively insignificant party with just twelve seats in the Reichstag and whose members were regarded as bullies.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Now he sat with recognized leaders of the bourgeois right and played a role at the Reich level.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Participation in the Reich Committee was for Hitler a great success.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In the NSDAP's own ranks, especially in the circles around Gregor and Otto Strasser, associating with the conservative right was controversial.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Joseph Goebbels noted in his diary: "Under the appeal are names!
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In Hitler's case one can only say: it hurts my soul to see you in such society." He saw the collaboration as compromising.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The cooperation, as the historian Otmar Jung points out, was not on Hitler's part based on sympathy with the conservative right but was rather purely tactical.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] By means of the initiative and the subsequent referendum, the political right made use of the particularly progressive plebiscite elements of the Weimar Constitution.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] According to Article 73, an initiative was successful if at least 10% of those entitled to vote approved it.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The Reich Committee's relationship to the people's legislative power was purely a means to pursue an aim.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Franz Seldte made this clear in a speech on 26 October: "The initiative is only a means of struggle.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] On 28 September 1929 the Reich Committee for the initiative against the Young plan submitted a bill to the Reich ministry of the interior that both the right wing of the DNVP around Hugenberg and the NSDAP had been involved in drafting.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] It stipulated that it was to be put to a popular vote if the Reichstag rejected it.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Reich Minister of the Interior Carl Severing (SPD) allowed the proposal to go forward in spite of reservations from within his own party.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] He assumed that a refusal would only play into the hands of the right wing and that the initiative drive would likely fail.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The draft was entitled: "Law Against the Enslavement of the German People".
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In its abbreviated form it was called propagandistically the "Freedom Law".
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The draft was divided into four paragraphs and went beyond reparations issues in the narrow sense.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] §1 rejected the recognition of war guilt.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] §2 demanded the abrogation of the corresponding Article 231 in the Treaty of Versailles and the evacuation of the occupied territories.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] §3 rejected accepting new reparation obligations.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] §4 stated that "Reich Chancellors, Reich Ministers and their authorized representatives who sign treaties with foreign powers in contravention of the provisions of § 3, para.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] 1 shall be subject to the penalties provided for in § 92 No.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] 3 of the Criminal Code." The clause referred to treason, which was punishable by no less than two years in prison.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Paragraph 4 in particular was included at Hitler's insistence.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The last paragraph was highly controversial even within the Reich Committee.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Hugenberg and the Agricultural League found the passage embarrassing and wanted to dispense with it altogether, but the NSDAP made its continued participation conditional on retaining it.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Hitler insisted on his position, and at the meeting of the Reich Committee on 21 September, the supporters of Section 4 prevailed.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The clause was, however, made somewhat less provocative.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In a first draft it would also have affected Reich President Paul von Hindenburg.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] While Joseph Goebbels and other National Socialists would have had no objection to including Hindenburg, the conservative members of the Reich Committee saw things differently.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The wording was therefore changed to exclude the Reich President.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Hindenburg nevertheless still refused to support the goals of the initiative.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] He rejected any connection with it and forbade using him or his name in the campaign.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] As a result, Hugenberg's propaganda was also directed against the head of state.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Hindenburg was called senile and it was claimed that he was a tool of the left and had no will of his own.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The right-wing parties made forceful use of propaganda to canvass for voters to take part in the initiative.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] One particularly effective slogan was: "To the third generation you must labor", using the German word *fronen*, referring to unpaid labor for a feudal lord.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The Reich Committee established a regular press service and published the series "Away with the Paris Tribute".
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] They also used such normal advertising media as posters and leaflets but relied primarily on the Hugenberg press.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Relatively new was the use of advertising films in the cinema for political propaganda.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Hugenberg gave a speech every other day and visited numerous cities throughout Germany during the first two weeks of the registration period.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Goebbels was similarly active, while Hitler made only a few public appearances.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The NSDAP held 7,000 meetings in October and often attracted unexpectedly large audiences.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] However, the campaign against the Young Plan overlapped with various state and local elections, and they were the priority for the party.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In addition to the Reich Committee there were local committees that were active in varying degrees.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Noteworthy was a large rally that took place on 1 September at the Hermann Monument near Detmold.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The committees used sometimes absurd conspiracy theories, such as claiming that the government could not have published all the provisions of the Versailles Treaty.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] There were rumors of "German citizens who would have to be sold abroad as something like wage slaves to work in the creditor states' colonies".
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The criticism of Versailles was also combined with anti-Semitic allegations and included completely false allegations such as claiming that the unmarried former Reich Chancellor Joseph Wirth was married to a Jewess.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Gustav Stresemann was defamed "as the epitome of all the dangerous tendencies of our nation ... whose psychological decadence is clearly derived from his political decadence." The NSDAP in particular pushed its position to the extreme during the period leading up to the initiative.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In the "*New Front*" published in the Ruhr area it said "that the National Socialist struggle against Stresemann would not stop at his grave!" At the 1929 Reich Party Congress, it introduced the concept of the "Un-German".
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] "The initiative creates ... two categories [of people]; the one that believes in a German future, the Germans, and the other that for some reason is against it, the Un-Germans." The extreme positions of the NSDAP and also of Hugenberg led to conflicts within the Reich Committee.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] There were also forces within the DNVP that were increasingly skeptical of the matter.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Some of the original supporters, such as the Agricultural League, turned away.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The Young German Order and even leading members of the former Freikorps also opposed the initiative.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Captain Hermann Ehrhardt, former leader of the violent Organisation Consul, called the action "a nonsensical prank" which would ultimately prove counterproductive for the nationalist camp.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Initially the Reich government was forced by the ongoing negotiations in The Hague concerning the Young Plan to act with restraint.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The political situation of Hermann Müller's 5-party coalition was difficult, and it left the field open to the agitation of opponents of the Young Plan.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Only after the first Hague conference in August 1929 did the government begin its countermeasures.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] It employed the United Press Department of the Reich government and of the Foreign Office.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Above all, the Reich Agency for Homeland Service played a major role.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The departments at the state level were instructed to pay special attention to the Young Plan.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In addition, the government set up a special press office.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In view of the strong position of the Hugenberg press, it had only limited success.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The period during which voters could register on the appropriate lists lasted from 16 to 29 October.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The Reich government spent a considerable amount of money on counter-propaganda.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In September 1929 the plan was to harness the parties, trade unions and other organizations close to the government.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The hope was for a thousand speakers from these groups and expenses of 250,000 Reichsmarks.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Total costs of 400,000 Reichsmarks were expected, some of which came out of the budgets of the Foreign Office and the Reich Chancellery, but most of the money came unbudgeted from the Ministry of Finance under Rudolf Hilferding (SPD).
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The state government of Prussia also joined the effort.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In addition to speeches and print media, radio and film were used for counter-propaganda.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The use of radio, which was state controlled but had been relatively apolitical until then, met with criticism even among government supporters.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In contrast, Reich Minister of the Interior Carl Severing (SPD) saw radio as a crucial propaganda tool.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Stations were required to broadcast so-called "instructional discussions" (*Auflagevorträge*) unchanged.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] A total of six were put on the air during the registration period.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] At some stations there was noticeable interference, but suspicions of sabotage could not be proven.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Prussian civil servants were forbidden to take part in the initiative and could face disciplinary action if they failed to comply.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The DNVP brought a legal action against the policy.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The Prussian State Court initially rejected the motion, but in the final decision, which was issued only after the election, the court recognized the right of civil servants to participate in a legal initiative.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Only active advocacy of the goals could be construed as official misconduct.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The parties in the government coalition were comparatively restrained.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The DVP, the party of the late Gustav Stresemann, fought most strongly against the initiative.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Shortly before his death he ruled out cooperation between the DVP and the Hugenberg-led DNVP on the grounds of the upcoming initiative.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The refusal, however, narrowed the party's political room to maneuver: "I see that we have to go with the left, because parts of the right in Germany have gone crazy." The position did not last long after Stresemann's death.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Severing took the clearest position against the initiative, with the result that the public saw the dispute as a battle between Severing and Hugenberg.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Severing initiated a public appeal by the Reich government entitled "To the German People".
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In it the content of the initiative was described as an "attempt at the worst kind of incitement of the people".
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] It declared its support for the Republic and for Stresemann's policy of rapprochement.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The appeal was signed by influential public figures, among them the economist and banker Hjalmar Schacht, industrialist Robert Bosch, physicists Albert Einstein and Max Planck, and the writers Gerhart Hauptmann and Thomas Mann.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Others such as entrepreneur Carl Friedrich von Siemens, independent politician Hans Luther and industrialist Carl Duisberg refused to sign.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] By the end of the registration period on 29 October, 10.02% of eligible voters had entered their names on the lists, 0.02 percentage points more than was needed for the initiative to succeed.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The Reich Committee was most successful in Germany's eastern states.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] East Prussia, Pomerania and Mecklenburg alone accounted for three quarters of all votes.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In accordance with the provisions of the constitution, the bill was debated in the Reichstag on 29 November.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The Reich Committee submitted an explanatory statement on the Freedom Act in which it once again presented its views.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Foreign Minister Julius Curtius of the DVP spoke for the government in Severing's stead.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The government wanted to make it clear that the dispute would not be a fight between Severing and Hugenberg or of a Marxist and an anti-Marxist.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Curtius accused the originators of the initiative of "throwing the constitutional order and separation of the Reich's political powers into complete disarray".
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The campaign, he said, was "an attack against the authority of the state".
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Speaking for the DNVP was not Hugenberg, who had not spoken in parliament for nine years, but Ernst Oberfohren and Axel von Freytagh-Loringhoven.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] During the debate a representative of the NSDAP made it clear that the party's participation in the initiative was a matter of the "abolition of the system by legal means".
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The position of the governing parties was presented by Thomas Esser of the Catholic Centre Party.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] He emphasized that the initiative wanted to replace "a policy of negotiation and understanding" with one "of sabotage and provocation".
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] As expected, on 30 November parliament rejected the bill by a large majority on its second reading.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Hugenberg did not have all members of the DNVP behind him in the vote.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] While they approved the first three paragraphs of the bill, it was not the same with the fourth paragraph which spoke of treason charges against ministers.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Hugenberg's intra-party critics around chairman Kuno von Westarp accused him of pushing a policy that exacerbated antagonisms and made cooperation with other middle-class parties impossible.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The threat of punishment in paragraph 4 of the Freedom Act hitched the party "to the wagon of the National Socialists", whose methods of agitation they rejected just as much as they did their social and economic policy demands.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] As a result, Hugenberg acted sharply against the dissenters, a move that contributed to a split in the party.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Westarp resigned, and some dissenters founded the "German National Association".
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] This gave rise to the short-lived Conservative People's Party.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The initiators now applied for a referendum to be held.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The Reich government deliberately set the date for it on 22 December, the last Sunday before Christmas, in order to keep the number of people voting low.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The referendum's sponsors again stepped up their propaganda.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] They were able to exploit statements critical of the government made by Reichsbank President Hjalmar Schacht as well as the state court ruling that allowed civil servants to participate in the vote.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In contrast, opponents of the referendum scarcely addressed the issue.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The Reich government judged the bill behind the referendum to be unconstitutional, which meant that adoption of the bill would require amendments to the constitution.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Passing the referendum therefore required the approval of more than 50% of those eligible to vote, whereas if the bill that had been constitutional, a majority of those voting would have sufficed.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] As it turned out, only 13.8% of eligible voters approved the referendum, barely more than in the initiative.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Thus the right-wing parties' campaign failed to reach its goal.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Overall, a comparison with the 1930 Reichstag election shows that there were correlations between a high approval rating for the referendum and a particularly strong showing by the NSDAP.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] On 12 March 1930 the Reichstag ratified the Young Plan by a vote of 270 to 192.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The failure of the campaign seemed to show the Republic's remarkable stability.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] But the propaganda that for months had attempted to tarnish the reputation of parliamentary democracy permanently altered the political culture.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Changes began to take place on the political right that ultimately led to the weakening of its more conservative forces in favor of the NSDAP.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Just how unstable the Republic was became apparent only a few months later with the onset of the Great Depression, the subsequent rise of the NSDAP and the final erosion of parliamentary democracy.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] One of Hugenberg's core goals was to use the campaign against the Young Plan to bring the political right together.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] This goal failed with the breakup of his own party and the founding of the People's Conservative Association, out of which grew the short-lived Conservative People's Party and the Christian Social People's Service.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In the Reichstag election of 1930, the Protestant conservative right was fragmented, and the DNVP received only 7% of the vote.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The party's closeness to the NSDAP, which had been emphasized during the campaign, made the formation of a middle-class bloc including the DNVP impossible.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] It marked the beginning of a development that contributed to the decline of the middle-class parties as a whole.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In retrospect the NSDAP appears to have been the real winner.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] At the end of 1929 and the beginning of 1930, it made gains in the state parliamentary elections in Baden and Thuringia as well as in the civic elections in Lübeck.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In January 1930 Wilhelm Frick in Thuringia became Germany's first NSDAP minister.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In the 1930 Reichstag election, the party's representation increased from 2.6% to 18.3%.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] With its participation in the Reich Committee, the NSDAP succeeded in breaking its previous political isolation.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] For the first time since 1923 Hitler played a significant role in German politics.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] A considerable body of research argues that Hitler's participation made him a potential alliance partner for the middle class political right.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] During the campaign and afterwards, the NSDAP received large amounts of money from industry, and that, the research says, played a significant role in the party's success in the Reichstag elections of 1930.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In addition, the Hugenberg press was from then on at Hitler's disposal.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The direct effect of the campaign on the rise of the NSDAP is, however, disputed.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Historian Otmar Jung in particular warned against overestimating it.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] According to his view, participation in the referendum in itself played only a minor role in the rise of the NSDAP.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Participation in the Reich Committee was associated with little money or additional propaganda opportunities for the party.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] According to Eberhard Kolb, the NSDAP was certainly able to draw on the financial resources of the Reich Committee.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] That made it possible for them, in the midst of the anti-Young Plan campaign, to organize the largest party congress to date with 200,000 participants and to uniform 20,000 SA men in September 1929.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Historian Gerhard Schulz early on emphasized that Hitler had succeeded in shaping his cooperation in such a way that he did not come across as an opportunist and could continue to be seen as a revolutionary radical.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The NSDAP became both a partner and a rival for the still powerful traditional right, especially the Stahlhelm.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The party's strategy was to avoid permanent ties to other groups.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] On the other hand, it was open to short term alliances if they contributed to its own strengthening.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In light of the campaign against the Young Plan, Josef Stalin demanded in September 1929 that the Communist Party of Germany (KPD) take a fundamentally different position on the reparations issue.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] He saw the campaign as the key to the NSDAP's sudden success.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] There were still reservations in the Comintern about a turn towards a nationalist-populist position, but they ended in 1930 in the face of further successes by the NSDAP.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In August of that year, the KPD newspaper *Die Rote Fahne* published a "Program Declaration for National and Social Liberation" in which the party used strongly nationalist language.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] The attempt to draw protest voters away from the NSDAP with national slogans failed.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] In the 1930 Reichstag election, the KPD barely made gains, while the NSDAP leapfrogged them by adding 95 seats.
[src:adolf-hitler/1929-german-referendum] Although 94.5% of valid votes were cast in favor of the proposal, voter turnout was only 15%, well below the 50% requirement, rendering the vote null.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in Germany on 14 September 1930 to elect the fifth Reichstag of the Weimar Republic.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] Despite losing ten seats, the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD) remained the largest party in the Reichstag, winning 143 of the 577 seats, while the Nazi Party (NSDAP) dramatically increased its number of seats from 12 to 107.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The Communists also increased their parliamentary representation, gaining 23 seats and becoming the third-largest party in the Reichstag.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The government of Chancellor Heinrich Brüning of the Centre Party lost its majority in the Reichstag as a result of the election.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] With President Paul von Hindenburg's support, his new cabinet became the first of the three presidential cabinets that governed through presidential emergency decrees rather than the parliament.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] After the 1928 German federal election, a five-party grand coalition was formed under Hermann Müller of the Social Democratic Party (SPD).
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] Following the collapse of the coalition on 27 March 1930, President Hindenburg appointed Centre Party politician Heinrich Brüning as chancellor.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] He formed a seven-party coalition government that was two seats short of a majority and did not include the SPD, the party with the most seats in the Reichstag.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] Brüning's government was confronted with the economic crisis caused by the Great Depression in Germany.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] He sought to balance the budget and stimulate exports through a policy of deflation which would require an unpopular policy of tight credit and a rollback of wage and salary increases (an internal devaluation).
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The Reichstag rejected Brüning's budgetary measures in July.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] With the backing of President Paul von Hindenburg, the bill was enacted using emergency powers allowed under the Weimar Constitution.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The Reichstag then overturned the emergency decree 236 to 222, with the yes votes coming from the Social Democrats, Communists, Nazis and a minority of the German National People's Party.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] At Brüning's request, Hindenburg dissolved the Reichstag on 18 July 1930.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The new election was held on 14 September 1930.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] For the purpose, the country was divided into 35 multi-member electoral districts.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] It was calculated via a three-step process on the constituency level, an intermediate level which combined multiple constituencies, and finally nationwide, where all parties' excess votes were combined.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The president was directly elected every seven years.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] He was head of the armed forces and had significant powers to dissolve the Reichstag, nominate a chancellor and invoke emergency powers through Article 48 of the Weimar Constitution.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] In 1930, Germany was formally a multi-party parliamentary democracy, with President Paul von Hindenburg (1925–1934) the head of state.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] However, beginning in March 1930, Hindenburg appointed governments without a parliamentary majority which systematically governed by emergency decrees, circumventing the democratically elected Reichstag.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The Centre Party shifted to the right after Ludwig Kaas became its leader.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The Nazi Party had increased their share of the vote in state elections since the 1928 federal election.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] In spring 1930, Adolf Hitler appointed Joseph Goebbels head of the party's Propaganda Division, and he oversaw the party's Reichstag campaign.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] Another 100,000 people joined the party between the election and end of the year.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The party had forty-nine newspapers, six of which were daily.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The SPD designated the "bourgeois block" of centrist parties and the Nazis as their enemies and, with the KPD, held rallies in Berlin on 1 August 1930 under the motto "Never again war".
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] Some 30,000 people participated in the SPD rally in the Lustgarten and 15,000 in the KPD demonstration at the Winterfeldtplatz.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] On 23 August, KPD members attacked a Nazi event in Bunzlau.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] Three people were killed and two seriously injured in fighting with the police.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The KPD election campaign climaxed with a rally in the Berlin Sportpalast on 12 September.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The election had a voter turnout of 82%, the highest since the 1919 election.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The Nazis increased their number of seats from 12 to 107.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The Social Democrats (SPD) remained the strongest party with 143 seats, a loss of 10 seats from the 1928 election.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The only other major party to significantly increase its seats was the Communist Party, which won 13% of the vote, securing 77 seats, 23 more than in the previous election.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The Centre Party increased their seat count by seven to 68 but dropped to fourth from third place in both seat count and popular vote when compared with the 1928 election.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The German National People's Party's (DNVP) support plummeted.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] They lost 32 of their previous 73 seats and dropped to fifth from second, chiefly due to the fragmentation of the party under Alfred Hugenberg's leadership.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] Due to his more hardline positions, moderate voters moved to the newly formed Christian Social People's Service (CSVD), Conservative People's Party (KVP), and Christian-National Peasants' and Farmers' Party (CNBL).
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The DNVP received 13% of the vote in rural areas, twice as much as it received in urban areas.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The German People's Party (DVP) continued to haemorrhage seats, losing 15 and only attaining 4.5% of the popular vote.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] They ceased to be a notable political force after the July 1932 elections.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The 28 other political parties shared the remainder of the votes.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] In his book *Political Man: The Social Bases of Politics*, Seymour Martin Lipset argued that the majority of NSDAP's new voters came from "liberal bourgeois center parties", which, with the exception of the Catholic Centre Party, lost almost 80% of their popular support.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] O'Lessker's counter-argument was widely debated and criticized by scholars such as Allan Schnaiberg, who argued that O'Lessker's interpretation of statistical data carried "major errors" and was of "questionable validity".
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The German National Association of Commercial Employees reported that half of its members voted for the Nazis.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] 184 of the seats in the Reichstag were held by parties that refused to participate in any coalition government.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The 1930 election left the Social Democrats and KPD with almost 40 percent of the seats in the Reichstag between them.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] In November 1931, the SPD suggested that the two parties work together, but KPD leader Ernst Thälmann rejected the offer, with the KPD newspaper *Die Rote Fahne* calling for an “intensification of the fight against Social Democracy”.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] Addressing the Nazi electoral breakthrough in the 1930 elections, Thälmann insisted that if Hitler came to power he was sure to fail and drive Nazi voters into the arms of the KPD.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] As late as February 1932, Thälmann was arguing that “Hitler must come to power first, then the requirements for a revolutionary crisis [will] arrive more quickly”.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] As a result of the election, Brüning was not able to form a majority in the Reichstag and continued to rule by decree, implementing harsh austerity measures that brought little economic improvement and were extremely unpopular.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] Governance by decree became the new norm and paved the way for authoritarian forms of government.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] Following the 1932 presidential election, the newly re-elected Hindenburg refused to sign any more decrees, and Brüning resigned.
[src:adolf-hitler/1930-german-federal-election] The success of the Nazi Party in the election lead to a number of differing reactions.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in Germany on 13 March 1932, with a runoff on 10 April.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Independent incumbent Paul von Hindenburg won a second seven-year term against Adolf Hitler of the Nazi Party (NSDAP).
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Communist Party (KPD) leader Ernst Thälmann also ran and received more than ten percent of the vote in the runoff.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Theodor Duesterberg, the deputy leader of the World War I veterans' organization *Der Stahlhelm*, ran in the first round but dropped out of the runoff.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] This was the second and final direct election to the office of President of the Reich (*Reichspräsident*), Germany's head of state under the Weimar Republic.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Under the Weimar Republic, which had arisen from Germany's defeat in World War I, the presidency was a powerful office.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Although the Weimar Constitution had provided for a semi-presidential republic, structural weaknesses and political polarization had resulted in a paralyzed Reichstag.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Combined with the Great Depression, this resulted in a government that had governed exclusively via presidential decrees since March 1930, giving the President much power.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hindenburg had been elected to the office in 1925 with the support of a coalition of several parties on the right who hoped that he would overturn the Weimar Republic, which was never particularly popular.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The Nazi Party had risen very rapidly, from being a fringe group for much of the 1920s to becoming the second-largest party in the Reichstag in 1930.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Led by Hitler, who exercised sole control over its policy and direction, its ideology combined extreme hostility towards the Weimar Republic with fervent antisemitism, anti-communism and German nationalism.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The threat of Hitler caused many on the left to support Hindenburg; at the same time, Hindenburg's failure to overturn the Weimar Republic had disappointed many of those on the right who had supported him in 1925.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The combined effect of these two influences resulted in a drastic change of Hindenburg's voter base between the two elections.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] In 1925 he had been elected as the right-wing candidate, while in 1932 much of his support came from the centre and left.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Some on the left were still lukewarm towards Hindenburg; the Communists exploited this by running Thälmann and promoting him as "the only left candidate".
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hindenburg failed to receive the requisite majority of votes in the first round, but was able to win reelection in the runoff.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hindenburg's reelection failed to prevent the NSDAP from assuming power.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Two successive federal elections later that year left it as the largest party in the Reichstag, and anti-republic parties in general holding the majority of seats.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Under this political climate, Hindenburg appointed Hitler as Chancellor of Germany in January 1933.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Upon Hindenburg's death in 1934 Hitler *de facto* assumed the presidency, which he combined with the chancellorship to become the *Führer und Reichskanzler*.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Therefore, the 1932 election was the last presidential election in Germany until 1949 (by which point the country was divided into West Germany and East Germany).
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] It remains, until today, the last direct election of the German President.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] All presidential elections after World War II have been indirect.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hindenburg remained the only independent politician elected president of Germany until the election of Joachim Gauck nearly 80 years later.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] World War I had resulted in the collapse of all monarchies in Germany.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] In place of the German Empire arose the Weimar Republic, named for the city in which its constitution had been drafted.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] It was never particularly popular among the various groups that constituted its political landscape, receiving lukewarm support even from those who supported democracy and being hated by extremists.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] According to the Weimar Constitution, the president was to be elected for a seven-year term by the people, though the first President, Friedrich Ebert, was elected by the Weimar National Assembly in 1919, as the situation in Germany was too chaotic to hold popular elections.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Ebert died suddenly in 1925, necessitating an election to be held that year, a year earlier than scheduled.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Paul von Hindenburg, the commander of the German military during the war, had won the 1925 election despite not running in its first round.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] He had defeated Wilhelm Marx, the candidate backed by the parties of the pro-republic "Weimar Coalition".
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] After 1929, the Great Depression devastated the Republic as parties argued over the proper response to it; the "Grand Coalition" government of Hermann Müller, which had been in power since the 1928 elections, dissolved in the face of the crisis and Müller resigned on 27 March 1930.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Heinrich Brüning, who was appointed Chancellor in his place, had no majority for his austerity policies in the Reichstag and began to use the Presidential powers to rule by decree.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] This was received positively by many conservatives who disliked democratic government and supported Hindenburg's reelection to further this conservative renaissance.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] At the same time, Hindenburg's work within the Republic had been much better than had been expected by pro-republican politicians.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The Nazi Party (NSDAP), originally called German Workers' Party (DAP), was founded in 1919.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] World War I corporal Adolf Hitler joined it later that year and became first its primary speaker and, in 1921, party leader with dictatorial powers.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hitler's preeminent position and infallibility within the party was confirmed in 1926 at a conference where the party manifesto was ruled immutable.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The party's ideology was a mixture of pan-Germanism, antisemitism, disgust with parliamentary parties, and resentment towards big business.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The DNVP and NSDAP made a formal alliance known as the Harzburg Front in 1930.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Nazi membership rose from 293,000 in September 1930, to almost 1.5 million by the end of 1932.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The amount of papers controlled by the party rose from 49 in 1930, to 127 by 1932.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] In prior elections the Nazis relied on membership dues, but started receiving financial support from businesses in 1932.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] It was permitted for a group to nominate a different candidate in the second round from the one they had in the first round.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hindenburg was 84 and had no desire to run for a second term, but he expressed interest in continuing office if his term was extended.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Brüning developed plans to evade direct elections by a Reichstag resolution to extend Hindenburg's time in office by amending the constitutional provisions requiring elections once every seven years.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hugenberg refused such proposals during the first week of January and insisted that an election be held per the constitution, a position that Hitler would also assume.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hitler was initially open to extending Hindenburg's term, but on the condition that Hindenburg dismissed Brüning, but he refused to.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] After elections were guaranteed, Hindenburg's cadre, led by Major General Kurt von Schleicher, courted the militant right's support of another Hindenburg candidacy.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] However, Hugenberg persuaded Der Stahlhelm to reject such proposals while the NSDAP supported a possible Hitler candidacy.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] This lack of support made Hindenburg reluctant to run for reelection, which worried both people who wished to preserve the Republic and those who supported Brüning's style of rule by decree.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Among those who signed the petition were the writer Gerhart Hauptmann, painter Max Liebermann, Artur Mahraun, leader of the Young German Order, the industrialist Carl Duisberg, as well as the former ministers Otto Gessler and Gustav Noske.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hitler was hesitant to run given Hindenburg's popularity and the fact that the NSDAP was still not the biggest party in the Reichstag.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Furthermore, he was not technically allowed to run as he lacked German citizenship, which was rectified upon his appointment to a post in the civil service of Braunschweig on 26 February.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] However, the Nazis were rapidly growing in popularity throughout late 1931, and Hitler was able to persuade industrialists that Nazism was compatible with capitalism.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hitler considered running Franz Ritter von Epp or Wilhelm Frick for the presidency.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The Nazi candidate was meant to be announced on 3 February at a meeting of the Gauleiters, but the party was still undecided.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Joseph Goebbels supported a Hitler candidacy while Gregor Strasser felt it would be dangerous as he could not defeat Hindenburg.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The Harzburg Front was starting to show disunity regarding the election, with the DNVP agreeing to support the Stahlhelm's choice of candidate in exchange for support in state elections.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hugenberg attempted to keep Hitler in line with the Harzburg Front at a meeting on 20 February, but to no avail; at a party rally on 22 February NSDAP member Goebbels revealed that Hitler would run in the race.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The Stahlhelm's choice – Theodor Duesterberg – was announced later that day, overshadowed by Hitler's candidacy.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Although Hindenburg preferred to have either been the right-wing or an apolitical candidate, he attracted the support of Republican parties in order to defeat Hitler.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The liberal parties – German People's Party and German State Party – declared their support for Hindenburg.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The Social Democrats and Brüning's Centre Party would support Hindenburg – in contrast to the 1925 presidential election, when Hindenburg had been the candidate of the political right and had been strenuously opposed by much of the moderate left and political centre.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] In 1932 this part of the political spectrum decided to unite with the moderate right in supporting Hindenburg to prevent Hitler's election.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The support of the moderate Weimar Coalition was also encouraged by the fact that, contrary to fears expressed at the time of his election in 1925, Hindenburg had not used his office to subvert the constitution, as Hitler now aimed to do.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Among those who had voted for Hindenburg in 1925 and refused to sign his petition were banker Walter Bernhard, Leipzig mayor Carl Goerdeler, and general August von Mackensen.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Duesterberg's candidacy attracted the votes of industrialists who would have otherwise voted Hindenburg for fear of Hitler.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] On 1 March the National Rural League (RLB), despite the best efforts of Hindenburg's campaigners, encouraged its followers to vote either Duesterberg or Hitler in order to remove the government of Brüning.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] In the first round on March 13 no candidate obtained an absolute majority of the votes cast, though Hindenburg with 49.6% failed only by a narrow margin.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] He scored higher election results in traditional Social Democratic and Centre strongholds such as the Prussian Rhine Province or Saxony.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hitler's results were a great disappointment to him, nevertheless the NSDAP recorded further gains compared with the 1930 Reichstag election.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hindenburg's failure to win reelection in the first round shocked and disappointed his supporters.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hitler outperformed Hindenburg in several of his 1925 strongholds, getting up to an estimated 50 percent of the vote of 1925 Hindenburg voters in the first round.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Taking Duesterberg's votes into account it has been estimated that Hindenburg retained fewer than a third of those who had voted for him in 1925, fewer than 30 percent excluding Bavaria, where the Bavarian People's Party (BVP) had endorsed him in both elections.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The expectations of the Communists presenting "the only left candidate" were not fulfilled, nevertheless they continued their fight against the policies of the Social Democrats and nominated Thälmann for the second round on 10 April.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] It was hesitant on the matter of Hindenburg's succession, positing that Hitler would inherit Hindenburg's supporters unless the question of reparations was settled.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The narrowness of Hindenburg's failure to obtain reelection in the first round made his reelection almost guaranteed in the runoff.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Nobody, especially Hindenburg's supporters, desired a runoff given that elections in several states would be held just two weeks later.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Still, a runoff provided another chance for Hindenburg's conservative supporters to promote him, especially as Duesterberg was likely to drop out.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] A meeting of Stahlhelm's executives on 19–20 March concluded that Duesterberg would not run in the runoff and that the alliance with the DNVP would be rescinded; many of Hindenburg's conservative supporters hoped that Duesterberg voters would mostly swing toward Hindenburg in the runoff.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] These hopes were increased by the fact that Hugenberg refused to endorse Hitler in the runoff, still sore over the latter's decision to run on his own.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hindenburg, Hitler, and Thälmann competed in the second round, after Duesterberg had dropped out.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] As in 1925, the Communist Party nominated Ernst Thälmann.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Backed by the Communist International, it was hoped that he would gain support from left-wing Social Democrats disgusted by Hindenburg's character.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Indeed, leftist splinter parties such as the Socialist Workers' Party of Germany and the *Internationaler Sozialistischer Kampfbund* organization declared their support, as did intellectuals like Carl von Ossietzky.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hindenburg's conservative supporters had not made any personal attacks against Hitler in the first round, although they criticized the NSDAP and its ideology.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] In the runoff they portrayed Hitler as a party man whose anti-republican rhetoric disguised the NSDAP's adherence to the system.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] They also portrayed Hitler and the Nazis as socialists whose rhetoric against Marxism was a disguise towards their own dislike of private property and free enterprise.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] They contrasted Hindenburg's Christian character with Hitler's apathy towards organized religion.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] However, the Nazis largely avoided attacking Hindenburg directly owing to his respect and popularity, and instead encouraged people to vote for him if they were satisfied with the unpopular Brüning.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The Nazis pioneered new campaigning tactics, such as direct mailing and transporting Hitler across the country by airplane, allowing him to perform at several rallies in a single day.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Furthermore, they would also hire venues that were deliberately too small in order to encourage overcrowding and present the perception of greater popularity for Hitler.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The events would last for several hours, with Hitler's actual appearance being delayed (accompanied by continual and misleading announcements on his time to arrival) in order to generate further crowd anticipation.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Industrialists who had supported Duesterberg were not enthusiastic about Hindenburg and did not largely cross over to him in the runoff, contrary to the hopes of his supporters.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Brüning was unpopular amongst industrialists such that after meeting Hitler on 19 March Reusch told the *Frankischer Kurier* to refrain from making any endorsements in the runoff.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Duesterberg endorsed Hindenburg in the runoff; nevertheless, the RLB, the Pan-German League, and the United Patriotic Leagues of Germany all endorsed Hitler in order to end the Republic.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Their relationships with Hugenberg were all consequently strained, and he asked the DNVP to not play a role in the runoff as he was increasingly isolated within and outside the party.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The industrialist Fritz Thyssen declared himself in favour of Hitler.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] About half of those who had voted for Duesterberg in the first round voted for Hitler while less than a third voted for Hindenburg.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Less than 15 percent of Hitler's gains came from defectors of Thälmann.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hindenburg, who owed his election to the support of the Social Democrats and the Centre Party, took the results with little enthusiasm.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] His failure to retain the votes of the vast majority of his 1925 supporters strained his relationship with Brüning irreparably, and he dismissed the chancellor on 30 May.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] This was a serious blow to those who had supported Brüning's style of presidential rule by decree.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Brüning's successor was Franz von Papen, an ally of Schleicher's who had no political experience or support in the Reichstag.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Schleicher and Papen courted the support of the Nazis by calling new Reichstag elections and lifting a ban Brüning had placed on the Nazi *Sturmabteilung*.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The NSDAP emerged from the Reichstag elections in July as the largest party ever seen in the Reichstag and having over a third of the vote, while Papen's position was undermined.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Papen dissolved the Reichstag again with elections in November, in which the Nazis lost seats but remained the largest party.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Although Papen retained the trust of Hindenburg and the army, he was widely unpopular and a strike by the Communists and Nazis enabled Schleicher, who had tired of him, to drum up fears and force Papen from office and become chancellor himself on 2 December.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] After two months of an ineffective Schleicher chancery, Hindenburg appointed Hitler chancellor on 30 January 1933 upon the recommendation of Papen.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The Reichstag fire of 27 February was used as a pretext by Hitler to issue the Reichstag Fire Decree, which nullified constitutional protections of free speech and other civil liberties.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Reichstag elections in March gave him a working majority, and he assumed dictatorial powers with the passage of the Enabling Act on 23 March.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hitler succeeded Hindenburg as head of state upon his death in 1934, whereafter he abolished the office entirely and replaced it with the new position of *Führer und Reichskanzler*, cementing his rule until his suicide during World War II in 1945.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Hitler's last will and testament once again separated the two offices, giving the presidency to Karl Dönitz and the chancellorship to Joseph Goebbels.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The resulting government, known as the Flensburg Government, governed but a tiny and rapidly receding part of Germany and was not recognized by the Allies.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] Upon the surrender of the German military they divided Germany into four zones, one controlled each by the British, French, Americans, and Soviets, and collectively governed the whole of Germany with the Allied Control Council.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] By 1949 three of the zones had coalesced into what became West Germany while the remaining Soviet zone became East Germany; both parts each had their own respective presidential elections starting that year.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] West Germany's constitution provided that the president be chosen indirectly by means of a Federal Convention consisting of parliamentarians and state delegates.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] East Germany's constitution provided that the president be chosen indirectly by a joint session of both chambers of parliament, though ultimately only a single person would serve as president before the post was abolished.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] In 1990, East Germany formally became a part of West Germany and was thus bound by its constitution; the first all-German presidential election since unification, and thus since 1932, was held in 1994.
[src:adolf-hitler/1932-german-presidential-election] The 1932 election is thus the last Presidential election by universal suffrage in Germany as of 2021.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler was born in Braunau am Inn in Austria-Hungary and moved to Germany in 1913.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] He was decorated during his service in the German Army in the First World War, receiving the Iron Cross.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1919, he joined the German Workers' Party (DAP), the precursor of the Nazi Party, and in 1921, was appointed the leader of the Nazi Party.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1923, he attempted to seize governmental power in a failed coup in Munich and was sentenced to five years in prison, serving just over a year.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] While there, he dictated the first volume of his autobiography and political manifesto *Mein Kampf* (lit.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] After his early release in 1924, he gained popular support by attacking the Treaty of Versailles as well as promoting pan-Germanism, antisemitism, and anti-communism with charismatic oratory and Nazi propaganda.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] He frequently denounced communism as being part of an international Jewish conspiracy.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] By November 1932, the Nazi Party held the most seats in the *Reichstag*, but not a majority.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Former chancellor Franz von Papen and other conservative politicians convinced President Paul von Hindenburg to appoint Hitler as chancellor on 30 January 1933.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Shortly thereafter, on 23 March, the *Reichstag* passed the Enabling Act of 1933, which ultimately began the Weimar Republic's transformation into Nazi Germany.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Upon Hindenburg's death on 2 August 1934, Hitler replaced him as head of state and thereafter transformed Germany into a totalitarian dictatorship.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Domestically, Hitler implemented numerous racist policies and sought to deport or kill German Jews.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] His first six years in power resulted in rapid economic recovery from the Great Depression, the abrogation of restrictions imposed on Germany after the First World War, and the annexation of territories inhabited by millions of ethnic Germans, which initially gave him significant popular support.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] One of Hitler's key goals was *Lebensraum* (lit.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] 'living space') for the German people in Eastern Europe.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] His aggressive, expansionist foreign policy is considered the primary cause of World War II in Europe.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On 1 September 1939, Hitler oversaw the German invasion of Poland, thereby causing Britain and France to declare war on Germany.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] After ordering an invasion of the Soviet Union in June 1941, he declared war on the United States in December of the same year.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] By the end of 1941, German forces and the European Axis powers occupied most of Europe and North Africa.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] These gains were gradually reversed after 1941 until the Allied forces defeated the German military in 1945.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On 29 April 1945, Hitler married his longtime partner, Eva Braun, in the *Führerbunker* in Berlin.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] They committed suicide the next day to avoid capture by the Soviet Red Army.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The historian and biographer Ian Kershaw described Hitler as "the embodiment of modern political evil".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Under Hitler's leadership and racist ideology, the Nazi regime was responsible for the genocide of an estimated six million Jews and millions of other victims, whom he and his followers deemed *Untermenschen* (lit.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and the Nazis were also responsible for the deliberate killing of an estimated 19.3 million civilians and prisoners of war.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In addition, 28.7 million soldiers and civilians died as a result of military action in the European theatre.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The number of civilians killed during World War II was unprecedented in warfare, and the casualties make it the deadliest conflict in history.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's father, Alois Hitler, was the illegitimate child of Maria Schicklgruber.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The baptismal register did not show the name of his father, and Alois initially bore his mother's surname, "Schicklgruber".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1842, Johann Georg Hiedler married Alois's mother.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois was brought up in the family of Hiedler's brother, Johann Nepomuk Hiedler.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois worked as a civil servant from 1855 until his retirement in 1895.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1876, Alois was made legitimate and his baptismal record annotated by a priest to register Johann Georg Hiedler as Alois's father (recorded as "Georg Hitler").
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois then assumed the surname "Hitler", also spelled "Hiedler", "Hüttler", or "Huettler".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The name is probably based on the German word *Hütte* (lit.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] 'hut'), and has the meaning "one who lives in a hut".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi official Hans Frank suggested that Alois's mother had been employed as a housekeeper by a Jewish family in Graz, and that the family's 19-year-old son Leopold Frankenberger had fathered Alois, a claim that came to be known as the Frankenberger thesis.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] No Frankenberger was registered in Graz during that period, and no record has been produced of a Leopold Frankenberger's existence, so historians dismiss the claim that Alois's father was Jewish.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In 2025, blood from the sofa in Hitler's study was used by Turi King of the University of Bath for DNA analysis.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The blood was confirmed to be Hitler's by comparing it to that of a male-line relative, and the DNA analysis also showed that Hitler did not have Jewish ancestry through his father.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] "If that was the case, we wouldn't have got the DNA match with him," King said.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Adolf Hitler was born on 20 April 1889 in Braunau am Inn, a town in Austria-Hungary (present-day Austria), close to the border with Germany.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] He was the fourth of six children born to Alois Hitler and his third wife, Klara Pölzl.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Three of Hitler's siblings—Gustav, Ida, and Otto—died in infancy.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Also living in the household were Alois's children from his second marriage: Alois Jr.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1892, the family moved to Passau, Germany, following Alois's promotion to the customs administration in Passau.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois was promoted and transferred to Linz, Austria, on 1 April 1893, but the rest of the family remained in Passau.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] There, Hitler acquired the distinctive lower Bavarian dialect, rather than Austrian German, which marked his speech throughout his life.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The family returned to Austria and settled in Leonding on 9 May 1894, and in June 1895, Alois retired to Hafeld, near Lambach, where he farmed and kept bees.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler attended *Volksschule* (a state-funded primary school) in nearby Fischlham.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The move to Hafeld coincided with the onset of intense father–son conflicts caused by six-year-old Hitler's refusal to conform to the strict discipline of his school.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois tried to browbeat his son into obedience, while Adolf did his best to be the opposite of whatever his father wanted.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois would also beat his son, although his mother tried to protect him from regular beatings.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois Hitler's farming efforts at Hafeld were unsuccessful, and in 1897, the family moved to Lambach.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The eight-year-old Hitler took singing lessons, sang in the church choir, and even considered becoming a priest.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1898, the family returned permanently to Leonding.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler was deeply affected by the death of his younger brother Edmund in 1900 from measles.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler transformed from a confident, outgoing, and conscientious student to a morose, detached boy who frequently clashed with his father and teachers.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Paula Hitler recalled that Adolf was a teenage bully who would often slap her.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois had made a successful career in the customs bureau and wanted his son to follow in his footsteps.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler later dramatised an episode from this period when his father took him to visit a customs office, depicting it as an event that gave rise to an unforgiving antagonism between father and son, who were both strong-willed.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Ignoring his son's desire to attend a classical high school and become an artist, Alois sent Hitler to the *Realschule* in Linz in September 1900.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler rebelled against this decision, and in *Mein Kampf* states that he intentionally performed poorly in school, hoping that once his father saw "what little progress I was making at the technical school he would let me devote myself to my dream".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Like many Austrian Germans, Hitler began to develop German nationalist ideas from a young age.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] He expressed loyalty only to Germany, despising the declining Habsburg monarchy and its rule over an ethnically diverse empire.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and his friends used the greeting "Heil", and sang the "Deutschlandlied" instead of the Austrian Imperial anthem.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] After Alois's sudden death on 3 January 1903, Hitler's performance at school deteriorated, and his mother allowed him to leave.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] He enrolled at the *Realschule* in Steyr in September 1904, where his behaviour and performance improved.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1905, after passing a repeat of the final exam, Hitler left the school without any ambitions for further education or clear plans for a career.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1907, Hitler left Linz to live and study fine art in Vienna, financed by an orphan's benefits and support from his mother.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] He applied for admission to the Academy of Fine Arts Vienna but was rejected twice.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The director suggested Hitler should apply to the School of Architecture, but he lacked the necessary academic credentials because he had not finished secondary school.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On 21 December 1907, his mother died of breast cancer at the age of 47; Hitler was 18 at the time.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1909, Hitler ran out of money and was forced to live a bohemian life in homeless shelters and the Meldemannstraße dormitory.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] He earned money as a casual labourer and by painting and selling watercolours of Vienna's sights.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] During his time in Vienna, he pursued a growing passion for architecture and music, attending ten performances of *Lohengrin*, his favourite of Richard Wagner's operas.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In Vienna, Hitler was first exposed to racist rhetoric.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Populists such as mayor Karl Lueger exploited the city's prevalent antisemitic sentiment, occasionally also espousing German nationalist notions for political benefit.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] German nationalism was especially widespread in the Mariahilf district, where Hitler then lived.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Georg Ritter von Schönerer became a major influence on Hitler, and he developed an admiration for Martin Luther.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler read newspapers and pamphlets that promoted prejudice and warned of an influx of Eastern European Jews, as well as writings by figures such as Houston Stewart Chamberlain, Charles Darwin, Friedrich Nietzsche, Gustave Le Bon, and Arthur Schopenhauer.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] During his years in Vienna he also developed strong anti-Slavic sentiments.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The origin and development of Hitler's antisemitism remain a matter of debate.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] His friend August Kubizek claimed that Hitler was a "confirmed antisemite" before he left Linz.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] However, the historian Brigitte Hamann describes Kubizek's claim as "problematical".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] While Hitler states in *Mein Kampf* that he first became an antisemite in Vienna, Reinhold Hanisch, who helped him to sell his paintings, disagrees.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler also sold some of his art through a Jewish businessman named Samuel Morgenstern while living in Vienna.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Many of Morgenstern's clients were Jewish; for example, a lawyer named Josef Feingold purchased several of Hitler's paintings of Vienna's historical architecture.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Evans states that "historians now generally agree that his notorious, murderous antisemitism emerged well after Germany's defeat in World War I, as a product of the paranoid "stab-in-the-back" explanation for the catastrophe".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler received the final part of his father's estate in May 1913 and moved to Munich.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] When he was conscripted into the Austro-Hungarian Army, he journeyed to Salzburg on 5 February 1914 for medical assessment.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] After he was deemed unfit for service, he returned to Munich.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler later claimed that he did not wish to serve the Habsburg Empire because of the mixture of races in its army and his belief that the collapse of Austria-Hungary was imminent.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In August 1914, at the outbreak of World War I, Hitler was living in Munich and voluntarily enlisted in the Bavarian Army.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] According to a 1924 report by the Bavarian authorities, allowing Hitler to serve was most likely an administrative error, because as an Austrian citizen, he should have been returned to Austria.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Posted to the Bavarian Reserve Infantry Regiment 16 (1st Company of the List Regiment), he served as a dispatch runner on the Western Front in France and Belgium, spending nearly half his time at the regimental headquarters in Fournes-en-Weppes, well behind the front lines.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1914, he was present at the First Battle of Ypres and in that year was decorated for bravery, receiving the Iron Cross, Second Class.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] During the war, he was saved by his commanding officer, Fritz Wiedemann, who pulled Hitler out of the rubble of a collapsed building while under heavy fire.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] During his service at headquarters, Hitler pursued his artistic interests, drawing cartoons and providing instructions for an army newspaper.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] During the Battle of the Somme in October 1916, he was wounded in the left thigh when a shell exploded in the dispatch runners' dugout.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler spent almost two months recovering in hospital at Beelitz, returning to his regiment on 5 March 1917.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] He was present at the Battle of Arras of 1917 and the Battle of Passchendaele.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] He received the black Wound Badge on 18 May 1918.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Three months later, in August 1918, on a recommendation by Lieutenant Hugo Gutmann, his Jewish superior, Hitler received the Iron Cross, First Class, a decoration rarely awarded at Hitler's *Gefreiter* rank.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On 15 October 1918, he was temporarily blinded in a mustard gas attack and was hospitalised in Pasewalk.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] While there, Hitler learned of Germany's defeat, and, by his own account, suffered a second bout of blindness after receiving this news.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler described his role in World War I as "the greatest of all experiences" and was praised by his commanding officers for his bravery.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] His wartime experience reinforced his German patriotism, and he was shocked by Germany's capitulation in November 1918.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] His displeasure with the collapse of the war effort began to shape his ideology.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The Treaty of Versailles stipulated that Germany had to relinquish several of its territories and demilitarise the Rhineland.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The treaty imposed economic sanctions and levied heavy reparations on the country.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Many Germans saw the treaty as an unjust humiliation.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] They especially objected to Article 231, which they interpreted as declaring Germany responsible for the war.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The Versailles Treaty and the economic, social, and political conditions in Germany after the war were later exploited by Hitler for political gain.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] After the war, Hitler returned to Munich.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Without formal education or career prospects, he remained in the army.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In July 1919, he was appointed *Verbindungsmann* (intelligence agent) of an *Aufklärungskommando* (reconnaissance unit) of the *Reichswehr*, assigned to influence other soldiers and to infiltrate the German Workers' Party (DAP).
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] At a DAP meeting on 12 September 1919, Party chairman Anton Drexler was impressed by Hitler's oratorical skills.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] He gave him a copy of his pamphlet *My Political Awakening*, which contained antisemitic, nationalist, anti-capitalist, and anti-Marxist ideas.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On the orders of his army superiors, Hitler applied to join the party, and within a week was accepted as party member 555 (the party began counting membership at 500 to give the impression they were a much larger party).
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler made his earliest known written statement about the Jewish question in a 16 September 1919 letter to Adolf Gemlich (now known as the Gemlich letter).
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In the letter, Hitler argues that the aim of the government "must unshakably be the removal of the Jews altogether".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] At the DAP, Hitler met Dietrich Eckart, one of the party's founders and a member of the occult Thule Society.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Eckart became Hitler's mentor, exchanging ideas with him and introducing him to a wide range of Munich society.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] To increase its appeal, the DAP changed its name to the *Nationalsozialistische Deutsche Arbeiterpartei* (National Socialist German Workers' Party (NSDAP), now known as the "Nazi Party").
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler designed the party's banner of a swastika in a white circle on a red background.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler was discharged from the army on 31 March 1920, and began working full-time for the party.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The party headquarters was in Munich, a centre for anti-government German nationalists determined to eliminate Marxism and undermine the Weimar Republic.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In February 1921, already highly effective at crowd manipulation, Hitler spoke to a crowd of over 6,000.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] To publicise the meeting, two truckloads of party supporters drove around Munich waving swastika flags and distributing leaflets.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler soon gained notoriety for his rowdy polemic speeches against the Treaty of Versailles, rival politicians, and especially against Marxists and Jews.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In June 1921, while Hitler and Eckart were on a fundraising trip to Berlin, a mutiny broke out within the Nazi Party in Munich.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Members of its executive committee wanted to merge with the Nuremberg-based German Socialist Party (DSP).
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler returned to Munich on 11 July and angrily tendered his resignation.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The committee members realised that the resignation of their leading public figure and speaker would mean the end of the party.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler announced he would rejoin on the condition that he would replace Drexler as party chairman, and that the party headquarters would remain in Munich.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The committee agreed, and he rejoined the party on 26 July as member 3,680.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler continued to face some opposition within the Nazi Party.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Opponents of Hitler in the leadership had Hermann Esser expelled from the party, and they printed 3,000 copies of a pamphlet attacking Hitler as a traitor to the party.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In the following days, Hitler spoke to several large audiences and defended himself and Esser, to thunderous applause.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] His strategy proved successful, and at a special party congress on 29 July, he was granted absolute power as party chairman, succeeding Drexler, by a vote of 533 to 1.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's vitriolic beer hall speeches began attracting regular audiences.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] A demagogue, he became adept at using populist themes, including the use of scapegoats, who were blamed for his listeners' economic hardships.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler used personal magnetism and an understanding of crowd psychology to his advantage while engaged in public speaking.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Historians have noted the hypnotic effect of his rhetoric on large audiences, and of his eyes in small groups.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Early followers included Rudolf Hess, the former air force ace Hermann Göring, and the army captain Ernst Röhm.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Röhm became head of the Nazis' paramilitary organisation, the *Sturmabteilung* (SA, "Stormtroopers"), which protected meetings and attacked political opponents.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] A critical influence on Hitler's thinking during this period was the *Aufbau Vereinigung*, a conspiratorial group of White Russian exiles and early Nazis.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The group, financed with funds channelled from wealthy industrialists, introduced Hitler to the idea of a Jewish conspiracy, linking international finance with Bolshevism.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The programme of the Nazi Party was laid out in their 25-point programme on 24 February 1920.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] This did not represent a coherent ideology, but was a conglomeration of received ideas which had currency in the *völkisch* pan-Germanic movement, such as ultranationalism, opposition to the Treaty of Versailles, distrust of capitalism, as well as some socialist ideas.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] For Hitler, the most important aspect of it was its strong antisemitic stance.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] He also perceived the programme as primarily a basis for propaganda and for attracting people to the party.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1923, Hitler enlisted the help of World War I General Erich Ludendorff for an attempted coup known as the Beer Hall Putsch.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi Party used Italian Fascism as a model for their appearance and policies.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler wanted to emulate Benito Mussolini's March on Rome in 1922 by staging his own coup in Bavaria, to be followed by a challenge to the government in Berlin.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and Ludendorff sought the support of *Staatskommissar* (State Commissioner) Gustav Ritter von Kahr, Bavaria's *de facto* ruler.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] However, Kahr, along with Police Chief Hans Ritter von Seisser and Reichswehr General Otto von Lossow, wanted to install a nationalist dictatorship without Hitler.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On 8 November 1923, Hitler and the SA stormed a public meeting of 3,000 people organised by Kahr in the Bürgerbräukeller, a beer hall in Munich.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Interrupting Kahr's speech, he announced that the national revolution had begun and declared the formation of a new government with Ludendorff.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Retiring to a back room, Hitler, with his pistol drawn, demanded and subsequently received the support of Kahr, Seisser, and Lossow.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's forces initially succeeded in occupying the local Reichswehr and police headquarters, but Kahr and his cohorts quickly withdrew their support.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Neither the Army nor the state police joined forces with Hitler.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The next day, Hitler and his followers marched from the beer hall to the Bavarian War Ministry to overthrow the Bavarian government, but police dispersed them.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In the failed coup, 16 Nazi Party members and four police officers were killed.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler fled to the home of Ernst Hanfstaengl and by some accounts contemplated suicide.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] He was depressed but calm when arrested on 11 November 1923 for high treason.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] His trial before the special People's Court in Munich began in February 1924, and Alfred Rosenberg became the temporary leader of the Nazi Party.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On 1 April, Hitler was sentenced to five years' *Festungshaft* ('fortress confinement') at Landsberg Prison.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] There, he received friendly treatment from the guards and was allowed mail from supporters and regular visits by party comrades.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Pardoned by the Bavarian Supreme Court, he was released from jail on 20 December 1924, against the state prosecutor's objections.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Including time on remand, Hitler served just over one year in prison.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] While at Landsberg, Hitler dictated most of the first volume of *Mein Kampf* (lit.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] 'My Struggle'; originally titled *Four and a Half Years of Struggle against Lies, Stupidity, and Cowardice*) at first to his chauffeur, Emil Maurice, and then to his deputy, Rudolf Hess.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The book, dedicated to Thule Society member Dietrich Eckart, was an autobiography and exposition of his ideology.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The book laid out Hitler's plans for territorial expansion as well as transforming German society into a dictatorship based on race.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Throughout the book, Jews are equated with "germs" and presented as the "international poisoners" of society.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] According to Hitler's ideology, the only solution was their extermination.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] While Hitler did not describe exactly how this was to be accomplished, his "inherent genocidal thrust is undeniable", according to Ian Kershaw.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Published in two volumes in 1925 and 1926, *Mein Kampf* sold 228,000 copies between 1925 and 1932.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] One million copies were sold in 1933, Hitler's first year in office.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Shortly before Hitler was eligible for parole, the Bavarian government attempted to have him deported to Austria.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The Austrian federal chancellor rejected the request on the specious grounds that his service in the German Army made his Austrian citizenship void.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In response, Hitler formally renounced his Austrian citizenship on 7 April 1925.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] At the time of Hitler's release from prison, politics in Germany had become less combative, and the economy had improved, limiting Hitler's opportunities for political agitation.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] As a result of the failed Beer Hall Putsch, the Nazi Party and its affiliated organisations were banned in Bavaria.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In a meeting with the prime minister of Bavaria, Heinrich Held, on 4 January 1925, Hitler agreed to respect the state's authority and promised that he would seek political power only through the democratic process.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The meeting paved the way for the ban on the Nazi Party to be lifted on 16 February.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] However, after an inflammatory speech he gave on 27 February, Hitler was barred from public speaking by the Bavarian authorities, a ban that remained in place until 1927.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] To advance his political ambitions despite the ban, Hitler appointed Gregor Strasser, Otto Strasser, and Joseph Goebbels to organise and enlarge the Nazi Party in northern Germany.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Gregor Strasser steered a more independent political course, emphasising the socialist elements of the party's programme.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The stock market in the United States crashed on 24 October 1929.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The impact in Germany was dire: millions became unemployed, and several major banks collapsed.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and the Nazi Party prepared to take advantage of the emergency to gain support for their party.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] They promised to repudiate the Versailles Treaty, strengthen the economy, and provide jobs.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The Great Depression provided a political opportunity for Hitler.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Germans were ambivalent about the parliamentary republic, which faced challenges from right- and left-wing extremists.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The moderate political parties were increasingly unable to stem the tide of extremism, and the German referendum of 1929 helped to elevate Nazi ideology.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The elections of September 1930 resulted in the break-up of a grand coalition and its replacement with a minority cabinet.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Its leader, chancellor Heinrich Brüning of the Centre Party, governed through emergency decrees from President Paul von Hindenburg.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Governance by decree became the new norm, paving the way for authoritarian forms of government.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi Party rose from obscurity to win 18.3 per cent of the vote and 107 parliamentary seats in the 1930 election, becoming the second-largest party in parliament.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler made a prominent appearance at the trial of two Reichswehr officers, Lieutenants Richard Scheringer and Hanns Ludin, in late 1930.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Both were charged with membership in the Nazi Party, at that time illegal for Reichswehr personnel.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The prosecution argued that the Nazi Party was extremist, prompting defence lawyer Hans Frank to call on Hitler to testify.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On 25 September 1930, Hitler testified that his party would pursue political power solely through democratic elections, which won him many supporters in the officer corps.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Brüning's austerity measures brought little economic improvement and were extremely unpopular.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler exploited this by targeting his political messages specifically at people who had been affected by the inflation of the 1920s and the Depression, such as farmers, war veterans, and the middle class.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Although Hitler had terminated his Austrian citizenship in 1925, he did not acquire German citizenship for almost seven years.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] This meant that he was stateless, legally unable to run for public office, and still faced the risk of deportation.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On 25 February 1932, the interior minister of Brunswick, Dietrich Klagges, who was a member of the Nazi Party, appointed Hitler as administrator for the state's delegation to the Reichsrat in Berlin, making Hitler a citizen of Brunswick, and thus of Germany.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler ran against Hindenburg in the 1932 presidential election.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] A speech to the Industry Club in Düsseldorf on 27 January 1932 won him support from many of Germany's most powerful industrialists.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hindenburg had support from various nationalist, monarchist, Catholic, and republican parties, and some Social Democrats.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler used the campaign slogan "*Hitler über Deutschland*" ("Hitler over Germany"), a reference to his political ambitions and his campaigning by aircraft.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] He was one of the first politicians to use aircraft travel for campaigning and used it effectively.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler came in second in both rounds of the election, garnering more than 35 per cent of the vote in the final election.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Although he lost to Hindenburg, this election established Hitler as a strong force in German politics.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The absence of an effective government prompted two influential politicians, Franz von Papen and Alfred Hugenberg, along with several other industrialists and businessmen, to write a letter to Hindenburg.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The signers urged Hindenburg to appoint Hitler as leader of a government "independent from parliamentary parties", which could turn into a movement that would "enrapture millions of people".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hindenburg reluctantly agreed to appoint Hitler as chancellor after two further parliamentary elections—in July and November 1932—had not resulted in the formation of a majority government.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler headed a short-lived coalition government formed by the Nazi Party (which had the most seats in the Reichstag) and Hugenberg's party, the German National People's Party (DNVP).
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On 30 January 1933, the new cabinet was sworn in during a brief ceremony in Hindenburg's office.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi Party gained three posts: Hitler was named chancellor, Wilhelm Frick Minister of the Interior, and Hermann Göring Minister of the Interior for Prussia.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler had insisted on the ministerial positions as a way to gain control over the police in much of Germany.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] As chancellor, Hitler worked against attempts by the Nazi Party's opponents to build a majority government.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Because of the political stalemate, he asked Hindenburg to again dissolve the Reichstag, and elections were scheduled for early March.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On 27 February 1933, the Reichstag building was set on fire.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Göring blamed a communist plot, as the Dutch communist Marinus van der Lubbe was found in incriminating circumstances inside the burning building.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Until the 1960s, some historians, including William L.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Shirer and Alan Bullock, thought the Nazi Party was responsible; now the view of most historians is van der Lubbe started the fire alone.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] At Hitler's urging, Hindenburg responded by signing the Reichstag Fire Decree of 28 February, drafted by the Nazis, which suspended basic rights and allowed detention without trial.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The decree was permitted under Article 48 of the Weimar Constitution, which gave the president the power to take emergency measures to protect public safety and order.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Activities of the German Communist Party (KPD) were suppressed, and 4,000 KPD members were arrested.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In addition to political campaigning, the Nazi Party engaged in paramilitary violence and the spread of anti-communist propaganda, in the days preceding the election.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On election day, 6 March 1933, the Nazis’ share of the vote increased to 44%, and the party acquired the largest number of seats in parliament.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's party failed to secure an absolute majority, necessitating another coalition with the DNVP.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On 21 March 1933, the new *Reichstag* was constituted with an opening ceremony at the Garrison Church in Potsdam.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] This "Day of Potsdam" was held to demonstrate unity between the Nazi movement and the old Prussian elite and military.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler appeared in a morning coat and humbly greeted Hindenburg.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] To achieve full political control despite not having an absolute majority in parliament, Hitler's government brought the *Ermächtigungsgesetz* (Enabling Act) to a vote in the newly elected *Reichstag*.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The Act—officially titled the *Gesetz zur Behebung der Not von Volk und Reich* ("Law to Remedy the Distress of People and Reich")—gave Hitler's cabinet the power to enact laws without the consent of the Reichstag for four years.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] These laws could (with certain exceptions) deviate from the constitution.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Since it would affect the constitution, the Enabling Act required a two-thirds majority to pass.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Leaving nothing to chance, the Nazis used the provisions of the Reichstag Fire Decree to arrest all 81 Communist deputies (in spite of their virulent campaign against the party, the Nazis had allowed the KPD to contest the election) and prevent several Social Democrats from attending.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On 23 March 1933, the *Reichstag* assembled at the Kroll Opera House under turbulent circumstances.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Ranks of SA men served as guards inside the building, while large groups outside, opposing the proposed legislation, shouted slogans and threats towards the arriving members of parliament.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] After Hitler verbally promised Centre party leader Ludwig Kaas that Hindenburg would retain his power of veto, Kaas announced the Centre Party would support the Enabling Act.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The Act was passed by a vote of 444–94, with all parties except the Social Democrats voting in favour.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The Enabling Act, along with the Reichstag Fire Decree, transformed Hitler's government into a *de facto* legal dictatorship.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Having achieved full control over the legislative and executive branches of government, Hitler and his allies began to suppress the remaining opposition.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The Social Democratic Party was made illegal, and its assets were seized.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] While many trade union delegates were in Berlin for May Day activities, SA stormtroopers occupied union offices around the country.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On 2 May 1933, all trade unions were forced to dissolve, and their leaders were arrested.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The German Labour Front was formed as an umbrella organisation to represent all workers, administrators, and company owners, thus reflecting the concept of Nazism in the spirit of Hitler's *Volksgemeinschaft* ("people's community").
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] By the end of June, the other parties had been intimidated into disbanding.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] This included the Nazis' nominal coalition partner, the DNVP; with the SA's help, Hitler forced its leader, Hugenberg, to resign on 29 June.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On 14 July 1933, the Nazi Party was declared the only legal political party in Germany.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The demands of the SA for more political and military power caused anxiety among military, industrial, and political leaders.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In response, Hitler purged the entire SA leadership in the Night of the Long Knives, which took place from 30 June to 2 July 1934.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler targeted Ernst Röhm and other SA leaders who, along with several Hitler's political adversaries (such as Gregor Strasser and former chancellor Kurt von Schleicher), were rounded up, arrested, and shot.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] While the international community and some Germans were shocked by the killings, many in Germany believed Hitler was restoring order.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On the previous day, the cabinet had enacted the Law Concerning the Head of State of the German Reich.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] This law stated that upon Hindenburg's death, the office of president would be abolished, and its powers merged with those of the chancellor.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler thus became head of state as well as head of government and was formally named as *Führer und Reichskanzler* (Leader and Chancellor of the Reich), although *Reichskanzler* was eventually dropped.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] With this action, Hitler eliminated the last legal remedy by which he could be removed from office.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] As head of state, Hitler became commander-in-chief of the armed forces.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On 19 August, the merger of the presidency with the chancellorship was approved by 88 per cent of the electorate voting in a plebiscite.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In early 1938, Hitler used blackmail to consolidate his hold over the military by instigating the Blomberg–Fritsch affair.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler forced his War Minister, Field Marshal Werner von Blomberg, to resign by using a police dossier that showed that Blomberg's new wife had a record for prostitution.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Army commander Colonel-General Werner von Fritsch was removed after the *Schutzstaffel* (SS) produced allegations that he had engaged in a homosexual relationship.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Both men had fallen into disfavour because they objected to Hitler's demand to make the *Wehrmacht* ready for war as early as 1938.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler assumed Blomberg's title of Commander-in-Chief, thus taking personal command of the armed forces.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] He replaced the Ministry of War with the *Oberkommando der Wehrmacht* (OKW), headed by General Wilhelm Keitel.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On the same day, 16 generals were stripped of their commands, and 44 more were transferred; all were suspected of not being sufficiently pro-Nazi.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] By early February 1938, 12 more generals had been removed.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler took care to give his dictatorship the appearance of legality.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Many of his decrees were explicitly based on the Reichstag Fire Decree and hence on Article 48 of the Weimar Constitution.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The *Reichstag* renewed the Enabling Act twice, each time for four years.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] While elections to the *Reichstag* were still held (in 1933, 1936, and 1938), voters were presented with a single list of Nazis and pro-Nazi "guests" which received well over 90 per cent of the vote.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] These sham elections were held in far-from-secret conditions; the Nazis threatened severe reprisals against anyone who did not vote or who voted against.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In August 1934, Hitler appointed *Reichsbank* President Hjalmar Schacht as Minister of Economics, and in the following year, as Plenipotentiary for War Economy in charge of preparing the economy for war.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Reconstruction and rearmament were financed through Mefo bills, printing money, and seizing the assets of people arrested as enemies of the state, including Jews.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The number of unemployed fell from six million in 1932 to fewer than one million in 1936.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler oversaw one of the largest infrastructure improvement campaigns in German history, leading to the construction of dams, *autobahns*, railroads, and other civil works.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Wages were slightly lower in the mid- to late 1930s compared with wages during the Weimar Republic, while the cost of living increased by 25 per cent.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The average workweek increased during the shift to a war economy; by 1939, the average German was working between 47 and 50 hours a week.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's government sponsored architecture on an immense scale.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Albert Speer, instrumental in implementing Hitler's classicist reinterpretation of German culture, was placed in charge of the proposed architectural renovations of Berlin.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Despite a threatened multi-nation boycott, Germany hosted the 1936 Olympic Games.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler officiated at the opening ceremonies and attended events at both the Winter Games in Garmisch-Partenkirchen and the Summer Games in Berlin.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In a meeting with German military leaders on 3 February 1933, Hitler spoke of "conquest for *Lebensraum* in the East and its ruthless Germanisation" as his ultimate foreign policy objectives.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler found Bülow's goals to be too modest.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In speeches during this period, he stressed what he termed the peaceful goals of his policies and a willingness to work within international agreements.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] At the first meeting of his cabinet in 1933, Hitler prioritised military spending over unemployment relief.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Germany withdrew from the League of Nations and the World Disarmament Conference in October 1933.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In January 1935, over 90 per cent of the people of the Saarland, then under League of Nations administration, voted to unite with Germany.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] That March, Hitler announced an expansion of the Wehrmacht to 600,000 members—six times the number permitted by the Versailles Treaty—including development of an air force (*Luftwaffe*) and an increase in the size of the navy (*Kriegsmarine*).
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Britain, France, Italy, and the League of Nations condemned these violations of the Treaty but did nothing to stop them.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The Anglo-German Naval Agreement (AGNA) of 18 June allowed German tonnage to increase to 35 per cent of that of the Royal Navy.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler called the signing of the AGNA "the happiest day of his life", believing that the agreement marked the beginning of the Anglo-German alliance he had predicted in *Mein Kampf*.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] France and Italy were not consulted before the signing, directly undermining the League of Nations and setting the Treaty of Versailles on the path towards irrelevance.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Germany reoccupied the demilitarised zone in the Rhineland in March 1936, in violation of the Versailles Treaty.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler also sent troops to Spain to support Francisco Franco and his Nationalist faction during the Spanish Civil War after receiving an appeal for help in July 1936.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] At the same time, Hitler continued his efforts to create an Anglo-German alliance.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In August 1936, in response to a growing economic crisis caused by his rearmament efforts, Hitler ordered Göring to implement a Four Year Plan to prepare Germany for war within the next four years.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] The plan envisaged an all-out struggle between "Judaeo-Bolshevism" and German Nazism, which in Hitler's view required a committed effort of rearmament regardless of the economic costs.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In October 1936, Count Galeazzo Ciano, foreign minister of Mussolini's government, visited Germany, where he signed a Nine-Point Protocol as an expression of *rapprochement* and had a personal meeting with Hitler.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On 1 November, Mussolini declared an "axis" between Germany and Italy.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] On 25 November, Germany signed the Anti-Comintern Pact with Japan.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Britain, China, Italy, and Poland were also invited to join the Anti-Comintern Pact, but only Italy signed in 1937.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler abandoned his plan of an Anglo-German alliance, blaming "inadequate" British leadership.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] At a meeting in the Reich Chancellery with his foreign ministers and military chiefs that November, Hitler restated his intention of acquiring *Lebensraum* for the German people.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] He ordered preparations for war in the East to begin as early as 1938 and no later than 1943.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In the event of his death, the conference minutes, recorded as the Hossbach Memorandum, were to be regarded as his "political testament".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] He felt that a severe decline in living standards in Germany as a result of the economic crisis could only be stopped by military aggression aimed at seizing Austria and Czechoslovakia.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler urged quick action before Britain and France gained a permanent lead in the arms race.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] In early 1938, in the wake of the Blomberg–Fritsch affair, Hitler asserted control of the military-foreign policy apparatus, dismissing Neurath as foreign minister and appointing himself as War Minister.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p01] From early 1938 onwards, Hitler was carrying out a foreign policy ultimately aimed at war.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In February 1938, on the advice of his newly appointed foreign minister, the strongly pro-Japanese Joachim von Ribbentrop, Hitler ended the Sino-German alliance with the Republic of China to instead enter into an alliance with the more modern and powerful Empire of Japan.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler announced German recognition of Manchukuo, the Japanese puppet state in Manchuria, and renounced German claims to their former colonies in the Pacific held by Japan.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered an end to arms shipments to China and recalled all German officers working with the Chinese Army.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In retaliation, Chinese General Chiang Kai-shek cancelled all Sino-German economic agreements, depriving the Germans of many Chinese raw materials.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 12 March 1938, Hitler announced the unification of Austria with Germany in the *Anschluss*.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler then turned his attention to the ethnic German population of the Sudetenland region of Czechoslovakia.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 28–29 March 1938, Hitler held a series of secret meetings in Berlin with Konrad Henlein of the Sudeten German Party, the largest of the ethnic German parties of the Sudetenland.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The men agreed that Henlein would demand increased autonomy for Sudeten Germans from the Czechoslovak government, thus providing a pretext for German military action against Czechoslovakia.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In April 1938, Henlein told the foreign minister of Hungary that "whatever the Czech government might offer, he would always raise still higher demands ... he wanted to sabotage an understanding by any means because this was the only method to blow up Czechoslovakia quickly".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In private, Hitler considered the Sudeten issue unimportant; his real intention was a war of conquest against Czechoslovakia.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In April, Hitler ordered the OKW to prepare for *Fall Grün* (Case Green), the code name for an invasion of Czechoslovakia.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] As a result of intense French and British diplomatic pressure, on 5 September, Czechoslovak president Edvard Beneš unveiled the "Fourth Plan" for constitutional reorganisation of his country, which agreed to most of Henlein's demands for Sudeten autonomy.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Henlein's party responded to Beneš's offer by instigating a series of violent clashes with the Czechoslovak police that led to the declaration of martial law in certain Sudeten districts.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Germany was dependent on imported oil; a confrontation with Britain over the Czechoslovak dispute could curtail Germany's oil supplies.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] This forced Hitler to call off *Fall Grün*, originally planned for 1 October 1938.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 29 September, Hitler, Neville Chamberlain, Édouard Daladier, and Mussolini attended a one-day conference in Munich that led to the Munich Agreement, which handed over the Sudetenland districts to Germany.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Chamberlain was satisfied with the Munich conference, calling the outcome "peace for our time", while Hitler was angered about the missed opportunity for war in 1938; he expressed his disappointment in a speech on 9 October in Saarbrücken.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In Hitler's view, the British-brokered peace, although favourable to the ostensible German demands, was a diplomatic defeat which spurred his intent of limiting British power to pave the way for the eastern expansion of Germany.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] As a result of the summit, Hitler was selected *Time* magazine's Man of the Year for 1938.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In late 1938 and early 1939, the continuing economic crisis caused by rearmament forced Hitler to make major defence cuts.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In his "Export or die" speech of 30 January 1939, he called for an economic offensive to increase German foreign exchange holdings to pay for raw materials such as high-grade iron needed for military weapons.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 14 March 1939, under threat from Hungary, Slovakia declared independence and received protection from Germany.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The next day, in violation of the Munich Agreement and possibly as a result of the deepening economic crisis requiring additional assets, Hitler ordered the Wehrmacht to invade the Czech rump state, and from Prague Castle he proclaimed the territory a German protectorate.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In private discussions in 1939, Hitler declared Britain the main enemy to be defeated and that Poland's obliteration was a necessary prelude for that goal.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The eastern flank would be secured, and land would be added to Germany's *Lebensraum*.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Offended by the British "guarantee" on 31 March 1939 of Polish independence, he said, "I shall brew them a devil's drink".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In a speech in Wilhelmshaven for the launch of the battleship *Tirpitz* on 1 April, he threatened to denounce the Anglo-German Naval Agreement if the British continued to guarantee Polish independence, which he perceived as an "encirclement" policy.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Poland was to either become a German satellite state, or it would be neutralised to secure the Reich's eastern flank and prevent a possible British blockade.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler initially favoured the idea of a satellite state, but upon its rejection by the Polish government, he decided to invade and made this the main foreign policy goal of 1939.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 3 April, Hitler ordered the military to prepare for *Fall Weiss* ("Case White"), the plan for invading Poland on 25 August.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In a Reichstag speech on 28 April, he renounced both the Anglo-German Naval Agreement and the German–Polish Non-Aggression Pact.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Historians such as William Carr, Gerhard Weinberg, and Ian Kershaw have argued that one reason for Hitler's rush to war was his fear of an early death.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] He had repeatedly claimed that he must lead Germany into war before he got too old, as his successors might lack his strength of will.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was concerned that a military attack against Poland could result in a premature war with Britain.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's foreign minister and former Ambassador to London, Joachim von Ribbentrop, assured him that neither Britain nor France would honour its commitments to Poland.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Accordingly, on 22 August 1939, Hitler ordered a military mobilisation against Poland.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] This plan required tacit Soviet support, and the non-aggression pact (the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact) between Germany and the Soviet Union, led by Joseph Stalin, included a secret agreement to partition Poland between the two countries.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Contrary to Ribbentrop's prediction that Britain would sever Anglo-Polish ties, Britain and Poland signed the Anglo-Polish alliance on 25 August 1939.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] This, along with news from Italy that Mussolini would not honour the Pact of Steel, prompted Hitler to postpone the attack on Poland from 25 August to 1 September.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler unsuccessfully tried to manoeuvre the British into neutrality by offering them a non-aggression guarantee on 25 August; he then instructed Ribbentrop to present a last-minute peace plan with an impossibly short time limit in an effort to blame the imminent war on British and Polish inaction.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 1 September 1939, Germany invaded western Poland under the pretext of having been denied claims to the Free City of Danzig and the right to extraterritorial roads across the Polish Corridor, which Germany had ceded under the Versailles Treaty.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In response, Britain and France declared war on Germany on 3 September, surprising Hitler and prompting him to angrily ask Ribbentrop, "Now what?" Britain and France did not act on their declarations immediately, and on 17 September, Soviet forces invaded eastern Poland.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The fall of Poland was followed by what contemporary journalists dubbed the "Phoney War" or *Sitzkrieg* ("sitting war").
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler instructed the two newly appointed Gauleiters of north-western Poland, Albert Forster of Reichsgau Danzig-West Prussia and Arthur Greiser of Reichsgau Wartheland, to Germanise their areas, with "no questions asked" about how this was accomplished.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In Forster's area, ethnic Poles merely had to sign forms stating that they had German blood.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In contrast, Greiser agreed with Himmler and carried out an ethnic cleansing campaign towards Poles.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Greiser soon complained that Forster was allowing thousands of Poles to be accepted as "racial" Germans and thus endangered German "racial purity".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] This inaction has been cited as an example of the theory of "working towards the Führer", in which Hitler issued vague instructions and expected his subordinates to develop policies independently.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Another dispute pitched one side represented by Heinrich Himmler and Greiser, who championed ethnic cleansing in Poland, against another represented by Göring and Hans Frank (governor-general of occupied Poland), who called for turning Poland into the "granary" of the Reich.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 12 February 1940, the dispute was initially settled in favour of the Göring–Frank view, which ended the economically disruptive mass expulsions.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 15 May 1940, Himmler issued a memo entitled "Some Thoughts on the Treatment of Alien Population in the East", calling for the expulsion of the entire Jewish population of Europe into Africa and the reduction of the Polish population to a "leaderless class of labourers".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler called Himmler's memo "good and correct", and, ignoring Göring and Frank, implemented the Himmler–Greiser policy in Poland.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 9 April, German forces invaded Denmark and Norway.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On the same day, Hitler proclaimed the birth of the Greater Germanic Reich, his vision of a united empire of Germanic nations of Europe in which the Dutch, Flemish, and Scandinavians were joined into a "racially pure" polity under German leadership.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In May 1940, Germany attacked France, and conquered Luxembourg, the Netherlands, and Belgium.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] These victories prompted Mussolini to have Italy join forces with Hitler on 10 June.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] France and Germany signed an armistice on 22 June.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Kershaw notes that Hitler's popularity within Germany—and German support for the war—reached its peak when he returned to Berlin on 6 July from his tour of Paris.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Following the unexpected swift victory, Hitler promoted 12 generals to the rank of field marshal during the 1940 Field Marshal Ceremony.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Britain, whose troops were forced to evacuate France by sea from Dunkirk, continued to fight alongside other British dominions in the Battle of the Atlantic.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler made peace overtures to the new British prime minister, Winston Churchill, and upon their rejection, he ordered a series of aerial attacks on Royal Air Force airbases and radar stations in southeast England.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 7 September, the systematic nightly bombing of London began.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The German Luftwaffe failed to defeat the Royal Air Force in what became known as the Battle of Britain.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] By the end of September, Hitler realised that air superiority for the invasion of Britain (in Operation Sea Lion) could not be achieved, and ordered the operation postponed.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The nightly air raids on British cities intensified and continued for months, including London, Plymouth, and Coventry.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 27 September 1940, the Tripartite Pact was signed in Berlin by Saburō Kurusu of Imperial Japan, Hitler, and Italian foreign minister Ciano, and later expanded to include Hungary, Romania, and Bulgaria, thus yielding the Axis powers.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's attempt to integrate the Soviet Union into the anti-British bloc failed after inconclusive talks between Hitler and Molotov in Berlin in November, and he ordered preparations for the invasion of the Soviet Union.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In early 1941, German forces were deployed to North Africa, the Balkans, and the Middle East.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In February, German forces arrived in Libya to bolster the Italian presence.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In April, Hitler launched the invasion of Yugoslavia, quickly followed by the invasion of Greece.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In May, German forces were sent to support Iraqi forces fighting against the British and to invade Crete.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 28 November, Hitler met in Berlin with Amin al-Husseini, the Grand Mufti of Jerusalem.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 22 June 1941, contravening the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact of 1939, over three million Axis troops attacked the Soviet Union.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] This offensive (codenamed Operation Barbarossa) was intended to destroy the Soviet Union and seize its natural resources for subsequent aggression against the Western powers.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The action was also part of the overall plan to obtain more living space for German people; and Hitler thought a successful invasion would force Britain to negotiate a surrender.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The invasion conquered a huge area, including the Baltic republics, Belarus, and West Ukraine.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] By early August, Axis troops had advanced 500 km (310 miles) and won the Battle of Smolensk.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered Army Group Centre to temporarily halt its advance to Moscow and divert its Panzer groups to aid in the encirclement of Leningrad and Kiev.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] His generals disagreed with this change, having advanced within 400 km (250 miles) of Moscow, and his decision caused a crisis among the military leadership.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The pause provided the Red Army with an opportunity to mobilise fresh reserves; the historian Russel Stolfi considers it to be one of the major factors that caused the failure of the Moscow offensive, which was resumed in October 1941 and ended disastrously in December.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] During this crisis, Hitler appointed himself as head of the *Oberkommando des Heeres*.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 7 December 1941, Japan attacked the American fleet based at Pearl Harbor, Hawaii.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Four days later, Hitler declared war against the United States.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 18 December 1941, Himmler asked Hitler, "What to do with the Jews of Russia?", to which Hitler replied, *"als Partisanen auszurotten"* ("exterminate them as partisans").
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The Israeli historian Yehuda Bauer has commented that the remark is probably as close as historians will ever get to a definitive order from Hitler for the genocide carried out during the Holocaust.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In late 1942, German forces were defeated in the Second Battle of El Alamein, thwarting Hitler's plans to seize the Suez Canal and the Middle East.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Overconfident in his own military expertise following the earlier victories in 1940, Hitler became distrustful of his Army High Command and began to interfere in military and tactical planning, with damaging consequences.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In December 1942 and January 1943, Hitler's repeated refusal to allow their withdrawal at the Battle of Stalingrad led to the near-destruction of the 6th Army.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Over 200,000 Axis soldiers were killed, and 235,000 were taken prisoner.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Thereafter came a decisive strategic defeat at the Battle of Kursk.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's military judgment became increasingly erratic, and Germany's military and economic position deteriorated, as did Hitler's health.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Following the Allied invasion of Sicily in 1943, Mussolini was removed from power by King Victor Emmanuel III after a vote of no confidence of the Grand Council of Fascism.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Marshal Pietro Badoglio, placed in charge of the government, soon surrendered to the Allies.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Throughout 1943 and 1944, the Soviet Union steadily forced Hitler's armies into retreat along the Eastern Front.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 6 June 1944, the Western Allied armies landed in northern France in one of the largest amphibious operations in history, Operation Overlord.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Many German officers concluded that defeat was inevitable and that continuing under Hitler's leadership would result in the complete destruction of the country.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Between 1939 and 1945, there were numerous plans to assassinate Hitler, some of which proceeded to significant degrees.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The most well-known and significant, the 20 July plot of 1944, came from within Germany and was at least partly driven by the increasing prospect of a German defeat in the war.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Part of Operation Valkyrie, the plot involved Claus von Stauffenberg planting a bomb in one of Hitler's headquarters, the Wolf's Lair at Rastenburg.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler narrowly survived because the staff officer Heinz Brandt moved the briefcase containing the bomb behind a leg of the heavy conference table, which deflected much of the blast.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Later, Hitler ordered reprisals, resulting in the execution of more than 4,900 people.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was put on the United Nations War Crimes Commission's first list of war criminals in December 1944, after determining that Hitler could be held criminally responsible for the acts of the Nazis in occupied countries.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] By March 1945, at least seven indictments had been filed against him.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] By late 1944, both the Red Army and the Western Allies were advancing into Germany.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Recognising the strength and determination of the Red Army, Hitler decided to use his remaining mobile reserves against the American and British armies, which he perceived as far weaker.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 16 December, he launched the Ardennes Offensive to incite disunity among the Western Allies and perhaps convince them to join his fight against the Soviets.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] After some temporary successes, the offensive failed.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In any case only those who are inferior will remain after this struggle, for the good have already been killed".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The same day, Hitler ordered the destruction of all German industrial infrastructure before it could fall into Allied hands.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Minister for Armaments Albert Speer was entrusted with executing this scorched earth policy, but he secretly disobeyed the order.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's hope to negotiate peace with the United States and Britain was encouraged by the death of US president Franklin D.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Roosevelt on 12 April 1945, but contrary to his expectations, this caused no rift among the Allies.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 20 April, his 56th birthday, Hitler made his last trip from the *Führerbunker* to the surface.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In the ruined garden of the Reich Chancellery, he awarded Iron Crosses to boy soldiers of the Hitler Youth, who were now fighting the Red Army at the front near Berlin.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] By 21 April, Georgy Zhukov's 1st Belorussian Front had broken through the defences of General Gotthard Heinrici's Army Group Vistula during the Battle of the Seelow Heights and advanced to the outskirts of Berlin.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In denial about the dire situation, Hitler placed his hopes on the undermanned and under-equipped *Armeeabteilung Steiner* (Army Detachment Steiner), commanded by Felix Steiner.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered Steiner to attack the northern flank of the salient, while the German Ninth Army was ordered to attack northward in a pincer attack.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] During a military conference on 22 April, Hitler enquired about Steiner's offensive.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] He was informed that the attack had not been launched and that the Soviets had entered Berlin.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered everyone but Wilhelm Keitel, Alfred Jodl, Hans Krebs, and Wilhelm Burgdorf to leave the room, then launched into a tirade against the perceived treachery and incompetence of his generals, culminating in his declaration—for the first time—that "everything is lost".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] He announced that he would stay in Berlin until the end and then shoot himself.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] By 23 April, the Red Army had surrounded Berlin, and Goebbels made a proclamation urging its citizens to defend the city.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] That same day, Göring sent a telegram from Berchtesgaden, arguing that as Hitler was isolated in Berlin, Göring should assume leadership of Germany.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Göring set a deadline, after which he would consider Hitler incapacitated.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler responded by having Göring arrested, and in his last will and testament of 29 April, he removed Göring from all government positions.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 28 April, Hitler discovered that Himmler, who had left Berlin on 20 April, was attempting to negotiate a surrender to the Western Allies.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] He considered this treason and ordered Himmler's arrest.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] He also ordered the execution of Hermann Fegelein, Himmler's SS representative at Hitler's headquarters in Berlin, for desertion.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] After midnight on the night of 28–29 April, Hitler married Eva Braun in a small civil ceremony in the *Führerbunker*.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Later that afternoon, Hitler was informed that Mussolini had been executed by the Italian resistance movement on the previous day; this is believed to have increased his determination to avoid capture.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 30 April, Soviet troops were within five hundred metres of the Reich Chancellery when Hitler shot himself in the head and Braun bit into a cyanide capsule.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In accordance with Hitler's wishes, their corpses were carried outside to the garden behind the Reich Chancellery, where they were placed in a bomb crater, doused with petrol, and set on fire as the Red Army shelling continued.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Grand Admiral Karl Dönitz and Goebbels assumed Hitler's roles as head of state and chancellor respectively.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On the evening of 1 May, Goebbels and his wife, Magda, committed suicide in the Reich Chancellery garden, after having poisoned their six children with cyanide.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The remains of the Goebbels family, General Hans Krebs (who had committed suicide that day), and Hitler's dog Blondi were repeatedly buried and exhumed by the Soviets.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's and Braun's remains were alleged to have been moved as well, but this is most likely Soviet disinformation.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] There is no evidence that any identifiable remains of Hitler or Braun—with the exception of dental bridges—were ever found by them.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] While news of Hitler's death spread quickly, a death certificate was not issued until 1956, after a lengthy investigation to collect testimony from 42 witnesses.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's death was entered as an assumption of death based on this testimony.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The Holocaust and Germany's war in the East were based on Hitler's long-standing view that the Jews were the enemy of the German people, and that *Lebensraum* was needed for Germany's expansion.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] He focused on Eastern Europe for this expansion, aiming to defeat Poland and the Soviet Union and then removing or killing the Jews and Slavs.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The *Generalplan Ost* (General Plan East) called for deporting the population of occupied Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union to West Siberia, for use as slave labour or to be murdered; the conquered territories were to be colonised by German or "Germanised" settlers.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The goal was to implement this plan after the conquest of the Soviet Union, but when this failed, Hitler moved the plans forward.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] By January 1942, he had decided that the Jews, Slavs, and other deportees considered undesirable should be killed.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The genocide was organised and executed by Heinrich Himmler and Reinhard Heydrich.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The records of the Wannsee Conference, held on 20 January 1942 and led by Heydrich, with 15 senior Nazi officials participating, provide the clearest evidence of systematic planning for the Holocaust.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 22 February, Hitler was recorded saying, "we shall regain our health only by eliminating the Jews".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Similarly, at a meeting in July 1941 with leading functionaries of the Eastern territories, Hitler said that the easiest way to quickly pacify the areas would be best achieved by "shooting everyone who even looks odd".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Although no direct order from Hitler authorising the mass killings has surfaced, his public speeches, orders to his generals, and the diaries of Nazi officials demonstrate that he conceived and authorised the extermination of European Jewry.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] During the war, Hitler repeatedly stated his prophecy of 1939 was being fulfilled, namely, that a world war would bring about the annihilation of the Jewish race.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler approved the *Einsatzgruppen*—killing squads that followed the German army through Poland, the Baltic, and the Soviet Union—and was well informed about their activities.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] By summer 1942, Auschwitz concentration camp was expanded to accommodate large numbers of deportees for murder or enslavement.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Scores of other concentration camps and satellite camps were set up throughout Europe, with several camps devoted exclusively to extermination.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The victims were killed in concentration and extermination camps and in ghettos, and through mass shootings.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Many victims of the Holocaust were murdered in gas chambers or shot, while others died of starvation or disease or while working as slave labourers.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In addition to eliminating Jews, the Nazis planned to reduce the population of the conquered territories by 30 million people through starvation in an action called the Hunger Plan.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Food supplies would be diverted to the German army and German civilians.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Cities would be razed, and the land allowed to return to forest or resettled by German colonists.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Together, the Hunger Plan and *Generalplan Ost* would have led to the starvation of 80 million people in the Soviet Union.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] These partially fulfilled plans resulted in additional deaths, bringing the total number of civilians and prisoners of war who died in the democide to an estimated 19.3 million people.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's policies resulted in the killing of nearly two million non-Jewish Polish civilians, over three million Soviet prisoners of war, communists and other political opponents, homosexuals, the physically and mentally disabled, Jehovah's Witnesses, Adventists, and trade unionists.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler never spoke publicly about the killings and seems to have never visited the concentration camps.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The Nazis embraced the concept of racial hygiene.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] On 15 September 1935, Hitler presented two laws—known as the Nuremberg Laws—to the Reichstag.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The laws banned sexual relations and marriages between Aryans and Jews and were later extended to include "Gypsies, Negroes or their bastard offspring".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The laws stripped all non-Aryans of their German citizenship and forbade the employment of non-Jewish women under the age of 45 in Jewish households.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's early eugenic policies targeted children with physical and developmental disabilities in a programme dubbed Action Brandt, and he later authorised a euthanasia programme for adults with serious mental and physical disabilities, now referred to as *Aktion T4*.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ruled the Nazi Party autocratically by asserting the *Führerprinzip* (leader principle).
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The principle relied on absolute obedience of all subordinates to their superiors; thus, he viewed the government structure as a pyramid, with himself—the infallible leader—at the apex.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Rank in the party was not determined by elections—positions were filled through appointment by those of higher rank, who demanded unquestioning obedience to the will of the leader.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's leadership style was to give contradictory orders to his subordinates and to place them into positions where their duties and responsibilities overlapped with those of others, to have "the stronger one [do] the job".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In this way, Hitler fostered distrust, competition, and infighting among his subordinates to consolidate and maximise his own power.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] His cabinet never met after 1938, and he discouraged his ministers from meeting independently.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler typically did not give written orders; instead, he communicated verbally, or had them conveyed through his close associate Martin Bormann.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] He entrusted Bormann with his paperwork, appointments, and personal finances; Bormann used his position to control the flow of information and access to Hitler.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler dominated his country's war effort during World War II to a greater extent than any other national leader.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] He strengthened his control of the armed forces in 1938, and subsequently made all major decisions regarding Germany's military strategy.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] His decision to mount a risky series of offensives against Norway, France, and the Low Countries in 1940, against the advice of the military, proved successful, though the diplomatic and military strategies he employed in attempts to force the United Kingdom out of the war ended in failure.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler deepened his involvement in the war effort by appointing himself commander-in-chief of the Army in December 1941; from this point forward, he personally directed the war against the Soviet Union, while his military commanders facing the Western Allies retained a degree of autonomy.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's leadership became increasingly disconnected from reality as the war turned against Germany, with the military's defensive strategies often hindered by his slow decision-making and frequent directives to hold untenable positions.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Nevertheless, he continued to believe that only his leadership could deliver victory.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In the final months of the war, Hitler refused to consider peace negotiations, regarding the destruction of Germany as preferable to surrender.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The military did not challenge Hitler's dominance of the war effort, and senior officers generally supported and enacted his decisions.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler created a public image as a celibate man without a domestic life, dedicated entirely to his political mission and the nation.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] He met his lover, Eva Braun, in 1929, and married her on 29 April 1945, one day before they both committed suicide.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In September 1931, his half-niece, Geli Raubal, committed suicide with Hitler's gun in his Munich apartment.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] It was rumoured among contemporaries that Geli was in a romantic relationship with him, and her death was a source of deep, lasting pain.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Paula Hitler, the younger sister of Hitler and the last living member of his immediate family, died in June 1960.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was born to a practising Catholic mother and an anti-clerical father; after leaving home, Hitler never again attended Mass or received the sacraments.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Albert Speer stated that Hitler railed against the church to his political associates, and though he never officially left the church, he had no attachment to it.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Speer added that Hitler felt that in the absence of organised religion, people would turn to mysticism, which he considered regressive.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] According to Speer, Hitler believed that Japanese religious beliefs or Islam would have been a more suitable religion for Germans than Christianity, with its "meekness and flabbiness".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Conway states that Hitler was fundamentally opposed to the Christian churches.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] According to Bullock, Hitler did not believe in God, was anticlerical, and held Christian ethics in contempt because they contravened his preferred view of "survival of the fittest".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] He favoured aspects of Protestantism that suited his own views, and adopted some elements of the Catholic Church's hierarchical organisation, liturgy, and phraseology.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In a 1932 speech, Hitler stated that he was not a Catholic, and declared himself a German Christian.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler viewed the church as an important politically conservative influence on society, and he adopted a strategic relationship with it that "suited his immediate political purposes".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In public, Hitler often praised Christian heritage and German Christian culture, though professing a belief in an "Aryan Jesus" who fought against the Jews.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] However, in *Hitler’s Table Talk* he was recorded as saying Christianity was an "absurdity" and nonsense founded on lies.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] According to a US Office of Strategic Services (OSS) report, "The Nazi Master Plan", Hitler planned to destroy the influence of Christian churches within the Reich.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Shirer commented that "the Nazi regime intended to destroy Christianity in Germany, if it could, and substitute the old paganism of the early tribal Germanic gods with the new paganism of the Nazi extremists".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] According to Bullock, Hitler wanted to wait until after the war before executing this plan.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Richard Steigmann-Gall has concluded there was no firm evidence of such a plan to replace Christianity.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Swedish historian Mikael Nilsson notes that many of Hitler's religious statements are sourced from *Table Talk*, which he considers highly unreliable: much of the content was written days after the event and was heavily modified to suit the agendas of Martin Bormann and later François Genoud.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Speer wrote that Hitler had a negative view of Himmler's and Alfred Rosenberg's mystical notions and Himmler's attempt to mythologise the SS.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was more pragmatic, and his ambitions centred on more practical concerns.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Researchers have variously suggested that Hitler suffered from irritable bowel syndrome, skin lesions, irregular heartbeat, coronary sclerosis, Parkinson's disease, syphilis, giant-cell arteritis, tinnitus, and monorchism.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In a report prepared for the OSS in 1943, Walter Charles Langer of Harvard University described Hitler as a "neurotic psychopath" and speculated that he exhibited masochistic tendencies and deep feelings of self-loathing, which he projected onto others, particularly Jews.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In his 1977 book *The Psychopathic God: Adolf Hitler*, the historian Robert G.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Waite proposes that Hitler suffered from borderline personality disorder.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The historians Henrik Eberle and Hans-Joachim Neumann consider that while he suffered from several illnesses, including Parkinson's disease, Hitler did not experience pathological delusions and was always fully aware of, and therefore responsible for, his decisions.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Sometime in the 1930s, Hitler adopted a mainly vegetarian diet, avoiding all meat and fish from 1942 onwards.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] At social events, he sometimes gave graphic accounts of the slaughter of animals in an effort to make his guests shun meat.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Bormann had a greenhouse constructed near the Berghof (near Berchtesgaden) to ensure a steady supply of fresh fruit and vegetables for Hitler.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler stopped drinking alcohol around the time he became vegetarian and thereafter only very occasionally drank beer or wine on social occasions.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] He was a non-smoker for most of his adult life, but smoked heavily in his youth (25 to 40 cigarettes a day); he eventually quit, calling the habit "a waste of money".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] He encouraged his close associates to quit by offering a gold watch to anyone able to break the habit.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler began using amphetamine occasionally after 1937 and became addicted to it in late 1942.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Speer linked this use of amphetamine to Hitler's increasingly erratic behaviour and inflexible decision-making (for example, rarely allowing military retreats).
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Prescribed 90 medications during the war years by his personal physician, Theodor Morell, Hitler took many pills each day for chronic stomach problems and other ailments.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] He regularly consumed amphetamine, barbiturates, opiates, and cocaine, as well as potassium bromide and atropa belladonna (the latter in the form of Doktor Koster's Antigaspills).
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] He suffered ruptured eardrums as a result of the 20 July plot bomb blast in 1944, and 200 wood splinters had to be removed from his legs.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Newsreel footage of Hitler shows tremors in his left hand and a shuffling walk, which began before the war and worsened towards the end of his life.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Ernst-Günther Schenck and several other doctors who met Hitler in the last weeks of his life also formed a diagnosis of Parkinson's disease.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] According to the historian Joachim Fest, Hitler's suicide was likened by numerous contemporaries to a "spell" being broken.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] According to the historian John Toland, Nazism "burst like a bubble" without its leader.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Kershaw describes Hitler as "the embodiment of modern political evil".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] "Never in history has such ruination—physical and moral—been associated with the name of one man", he adds.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's political programme brought about a world war, leaving behind a devastated and impoverished Eastern and Central Europe.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Germany suffered wholesale destruction, characterised as *Stunde Null* (Zero Hour).
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's policies inflicted human suffering on an unprecedented scale; according to R.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Rummel, the Nazi regime was responsible for the democidal killing of an estimated 19.3 million civilians and prisoners of war.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In addition, 28.7 million soldiers and civilians died as a result of military action in the European theatre of World War II.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The number of civilians killed during the Second World War was unprecedented in the history of warfare.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Historians, philosophers, and politicians often use the word "evil" to describe the Nazi regime.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Many European countries have criminalised both the promotion of Nazism and Holocaust denial.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The historian Friedrich Meinecke described Hitler as "one of the great examples of the singular and incalculable power of personality in historical life".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The English historian Hugh Trevor-Roper saw him as "among the 'terrible simplifiers' of history, the most systematic, the most historical, the most philosophical, and yet the coarsest, cruelest, least magnanimous conqueror the world has ever known".
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Roberts, Hitler's defeat marked the end of a phase of European history dominated by Germany.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] In its place emerged the Cold War, a global confrontation between the Western Bloc, dominated by the United States and other NATO nations, and the Eastern Bloc, dominated by the Soviet Union.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] The historian Sebastian Haffner asserted that without Hitler and the displacement of the Jews, the modern nation-state of Israel would not exist.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] He contends that without Hitler, the de-colonisation of former European spheres of influence would have been postponed.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Further, Haffner claimed that other than Alexander the Great, Hitler had a more significant impact than any other comparable historical figure, in that he too caused a wide range of worldwide changes in a relatively short time span.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler exploited documentary films and newsreels to inspire a cult of personality.
[src:adolf-hitler/adolf-hitler-p02] He was involved and appeared in a series of propaganda films throughout his political career, many made by Leni Riefenstahl, regarded as a pioneer of modern filmmaking.
